<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Jerusalem Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton today
condemned bombings in Jerusalem that killed at least 18 people,
saying it was a "barbarous act."
</P>
<P>
The explosions occurred in the afternoon in Jerusalem at a
crowded outdoor vegetable market, killing at least 18 and wounding
more than 150. There was no immediate claim of responsibility for
the attacks.
</P>
<P>
"The slaughter was aimed directly at innocent Israelis,"
Clinton said in a statement at the White House briefing room. "It
was also aimed at the majority of Israelis, Palestinians and Arabs
who want a lasting and just peace."
</P>
<P>
"We must not let the enemies of peace prevail," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Clinton telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to express his condolences.
</P>
<P>
"I told him the hearts and prayers of Americans are with him,
the people of Israel, and the victims of the attack and their
families," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also announced postponement of plans to send special
U.S. mediator Dennis Ross to the Middle East until a period of
mourning can be observed. Ross had been scheduled to depart for
Israel tonight.
</P>
<P>
"The trip (of Ross) will be postponed for a period -- an
appropriate period of mourning," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would continue his efforts to push forward the
Middle East peace process and any suggestion that he was not
"personally involved" was false.
</P>
<P>
"I believe my personal involvement has been continuing and
intense in this (peace process)," he said. "But I know of no
example in recent history where peace is made by third parties
trying to be helpful, making public statements alone." 
</P>
</TEXT>
