<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's President-Elect to Be Sworn in August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Iran's President-elect Mohammad
Khatami will be sworn in as the country's fifth president on
August 4, Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a formal session of the parliament, Nateq-Nouri
said the swearing-in ceremony would take place at nine o'clock
that morning.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to be attended by outgoing President Hashemi
Rafsanjani, head of the Judiciary Mohammad Yazdi, top civilian and
military officials, leaders of the religious minorities and the
diplomatic corps in the capital of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
According to parliament procedure, the new president is
required, with two weeks after inauguration, to introduce his
cabinet as well as his administrative program to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The parliament will start study of the program and
composition of the cabinet in three five-hour sessions within one
week and the cast ballots in a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
So far, the president-elect has been withholding the make-up of
his government.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that Iran's Permanent Representative at
the United Nations, Kamal Kharrazi, will be the next foreign
minister to replace Ali Akbar Velayati, who held the post for 16
years.
</P>
<P>
First Vice-President Hassan Habibi is to be renominated for
the post to ensure continuation of the development programs under
the Rafsanjani government.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President for executive affairs Mohammad Hashemi, who is
brother of Rafsanjani, will likely maintain his position and
Mohammad Ali Najafi, currently Minister of Education, may take
over as head of the Plan and Budget Organization.
</P>
<P>
Mostafa Hashemitaba, vice-president for physical training
affairs, will probably retain his post, while Admiral Ali
Shamkhani will become defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, 54, won a landslide victory over his main rival
Nateq-Nouri during the May 23 presidential election, in which the
most massive turnout since the victory of the 1979 Islamic
Revolution was recorded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
