<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Remains Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan opposition remains split
when FORD-Asili Chairman Kenneth Matiba today rejected other
opposition leaders' stand to have the National Convention
Executive Council (NCEC) to lead their talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the only way forward is for a constitutional
conference that is convened and managed by the religious
institutions in the country," Matiba said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"The conference must have a neutral chair, a neutral venue and
an open floor," noted Matiba, charging both the parliament and
the NCEC are strongly biased and thus do not represent the views
of Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
NCEC, an umbrella body set up in April by Opposition parties
to coordinate their campaign for reforms, now is an interested
party which cannot represent the Opposition in the reforms debate
with President Daniel arap Moi, Matiba stressed.
</P>
<P>
Main Opposition leaders, including several FORD-Asili members
of parliament, reached agreement last week to undertake the
dialogue through NCEC and within the institutional framework the
NCEC provides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Matiba called on Moi to step down within five days
beginning today, otherwise FORD-Asili would begin mass action
including the boycott of shops and businesses, especially those
owned by Asian Kenyans, he said.
</P>
<P>
Matiba also vowed to take action to press for a fresh
population census, the establishment of an independent electoral
commission, free access by political parties to media, redrawing
of constituency boundaries and so on.
</P>
<P>
FORD-Asili is one of the five registered Opposition parties in
the east African country but its leader Matiba, a member of
parliament, did not register as a voter during the voter
registration held from May to June.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has so far failed to pick a team to discuss
constitutional reforms with the government since Moi softened his
stance by meeting with official Opposition leader Kijana Wamalwa
and 19 key religious leaders and pledging dialogue in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The government's shifts of position came days after the most
violent conflicts between the police and the Opposition
supporters in seven years broke out, claiming 13 lives around the
country on July 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
