<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Armed Forces to Maintain Global Military Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said here today that the new Labor government would seek
to make the country's armed forces continue to play a global role.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the House of Commons' defense committee early today,
Robertson said, "We have to keep a broad balance of capabilities
so we can do what the people want us to do. What we have rejected
is the idea of minimal defense."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Britain should maintain its armed forces in a
rapidly changing world. "In Europe today, we can see how
instability can so easily escalate into major conflict with
consequences which spill over borders and threaten our own
national security," he said.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary pledged that the coutry's defense
spending would not be slashed but he made it clear the military
would have to make better use of its budget.
</P>
<P>
"The British people want strong defense for this country but
they don't want defense at any price and we must justify every
pound which is spent in the defense budget," he said.
</P>
<P>
Writing in today's Independent Newspaper, Robertson said, "We
are going to examine whether Britain should spend the money to
have a substantial role in situations like Bosnia or other
international crises."
</P>
<P>
He said, "With the end of the Cold War we have the opportunity
to decide what kind of contribution we wish to make to
international security."
</P>
<P>
"In truth, the British people want Britain to play a
substantial role in NATO, and to play a wider role in
international politics," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
