<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Export Earnings Decline Last Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Export earnings for the
country went down by 10.6 percent as import bill increased by
24.6 percent last June, the Bank of Tanzania (BoT) disclosed
today.
</P>
<P>
The BoT said in its monthly economic review report that export
earnings dropped largely due to a decrease of 24.6 percent in
traditional exports and a decline of 2.3 percent in
non-traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
The BoT explained in the report issued here that the level of
receipts from traditional exports was low on account of a
decrease in both the volume and unit prices.
</P>
<P>
It said coffee was the only traditional crop which realized
increase in export earnings by one percent while others such as
cotton, sisal, tea, tobacco and cashew nuts registered decreases
in export volumes.
</P>
<P>
The BoT report, however, said sisal and tobacco enjoyed higher
export unit prices, but the sharp decline in export volume led to
lower earnings from tobacco.
</P>
<P>
It said the overall decrease in export volume was the major
factor for the poor performance of traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
On imports, the report said the major reasons for the increase
recorded was due to increases in all major categories, namely,
capital goods, intermediate goods, and consumer goods which
increased by 9.8 percent, 68 percent and 6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhilets, the report said there was a surge in the imports of
building and construction equipment and machinery within the
capital goods category, which was an indication of expanding
investment activities in both construction and the manufacturing
sector.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated that imports of food and food stuffs
increased by 102.3 percent during June, while other consumer
goods declined by nearly 4 percent to 21 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The BoT said in its report that the government's budgetary
performance last month was outstanding, with revenue collection
picking up from 46.3 billion Tanzania shillings (about 77 million
US Dollars) in May to 57.2 billion T. Shs. (about 95 million US
Dollars) and expenditure stagnating at around 52 billion T. Shs
(about 86 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
It said the favorable situation improved the monthly overall
balance from a deficit of 5.8 billion T. Shs. (about 9.6 million
US Dollars) in May to a surplus of 4.6 billion T. Shs. (about 7.6
million US Dollars), while revenue collection reached 572 billion
T. Shs. (about 953 million US Dollars) in 1996/97, equivalent to
17.3 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the records compared favorably with the revenue
target for the year, which was 563.8 billion T. Shs. (about 939
million US Dollars) or 17.1 percent of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Bombs Kill 14 in Jerusalem, Setting Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- In a major setback to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, two suspected Palestinian
suicide bombers blew themselves up in a bustling Jerusalem market
today, killing 14 people and injuring 170 others.
</P>
<P>
This was the first suicide bombing attack since the March 22
suicide bombing of a Tel Aviv cafe and one of the worst terror
attacks against Israel since the peace process began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Two loud explosions occurred in seconds apart around 1:15
p.m. local time in the Mahane Yehuda open market, which was
packed with customers shopping for vegetables, fruits and other
daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said that they saw two Palestinians wearing
shirts and ties entering the market, each carrying a huge bag
which police investigators late estimated to contain 10 kilograms
of explosives. One of them sat in front of a store at the
junction linking the market to the busy Jaffa Street and
detonated his bomb, and 20 seconds later another bomber blew
himself up.
</P>
<P>
Police said at least 14 people, including the two bombers,
were killed and 170 others were wounded in the blasts, which
badly devastated the nearby stores and cut down people from all
directions.
</P>
<P>
The scene was covered with bodies, blood and debris, and the
crowd there was chaotic, panic and hysteric as the wounded and
shocked survivors screamed and cried. Ambulances, police and
rescue workers quickly rushed to the site to evacuate the wounded
and collect body parts of some worst hit victims.
</P>
<P>
Police immediately sealed off the market area and ordered
the closure of the shops in order to search for more bombs
with bomb-sniffing dogs, but no other bombs were found.
</P>
<P>
So far, no one has claimed responsibility for the attacks,
though police suspected them to be carried out by anti-Israeli
extremist Palestinian organizations. Suicide bombings in Israel
were usually carried out by two militant Islamic organizations
the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and the smaller Islamic
Jihad. From late February to early March last year, they
launched a wave of suicide bombing attacks in public buses
in Jerusalem, Tel Aviv and Ashkelon, killing 62 people and
wounding hundreds others.
</P>
<P>
A large crowd gathered near the scene, many of them were
anxious to know whether any members of their family or relatives
were killed or wounded. Scores of ultra-rightist demonstrators
held a demonstration, shouting "Death to Arabs" and calling for
the government to end the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Police had to escort the Arab workers employed at the market
out of the area for fear that the extremist Jews would carry out
revenge attacks against them. Two leaders of the ultra-rightist
Kache Movement and three other demonstrators were arrested by the
police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-30 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
