<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-30 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Bombs Kill 14 in Jerusalem, Setting Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 30 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Reactions were swiftly coming from all sides. Israeli
government strongly condemned the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) for refusing to crack down on anti-Israeli terrorism and
even encouraging it. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu held
immediate consulations with senior ministers, including Foreign
Minister David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman David Bar-Illan blamed the PNA for the
attacks, warning the peace process could not continue as long as
the terrorism was not eliminated. But he fell short of declaring
to cancel the planned resumption of the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks within the week.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat telephoned both Netanyahu and
Israeli President Ezer Weizman to condemn the attacks as "a crime
against the peace process." He offered condolences to the
victims, adding that much more needed to be done to prevent
further terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu told Arafat that condolences were not
enough and the PNA should make a U-turn in both his words and
actions by taking concrete measures to stamp out terrorism. In a
news conference held late the afternoon, Netanyahu demanded the
PNA act to crack down not only terrorist organizations, but
also the infrastructure that support them.
</P>
<P>
PNA officials called on Israeli government to act with
sanity and reason and to proceed with the peace process so
to stamp out the terrorism. Chief Palestinian Negotiator Saeb
Erekat said the PNA has been and will be doing 100 percent
to fight terrorism. He said the only answer to terrorism
should be for both Israelis and Palestinians to send out a
strong message by resuming and advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
For security reasons, Israeli troops reimposed a total
closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and ordered over
50,000 Palestinians working in Israel to return home. And all
Israelis were barred from entering the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The bombing attacks also were condemned by international
leaders. U.S. President Bill Clinton called them a "barbarous
act" against innocent people. He called on the PNA to take
concrete actions to crack down on terrorism and increase
security cooperation with Israel. He said the only answer to
terrorism should be deepening determination by both Israel and
the PNA to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh said Jordan condemned
and categorically rejected such acts of terrorism. He also
hoped that the peace process would continue despite the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak phoned Netanyahu today to
express condolences and the hope that the peace process would
continue.
</P>
<P>
Today's bombings came at a time when the Palestinians and
Israelis had agreed to resume peace talks this week, giving hope
to break the prolonged deadlock in the peace talks, which have
been stalled since Israel started building the Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The long-term implications of the bombings remained unclear
at the time, but the immediate setback was the cancellation
of a planned visit here tomorrow by U.S. special peace envoy
Dennis Ross on a new round of mediation. Washington announced
to delay Ross' mission shortly after the bombing attacks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that even if lower-level talks would be
resumed as scheduled, no major progress could be made when
the two sides remained dubious about each other's commitments
to peace.
</P>
<P>
The bombings, worst since Israel's hardline Likud government
came to power over one year ago, also tested Netanyahu's
election promises to bring the nation peace with security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-30 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Condemns Bomb Attack in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus issued a statement today
strongly condemning the bomb attack in Jerusalem earlier in the
day, which left 14 people dead and more than 150 injured.
</P>
<P>
In the statement issued here this evening, the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs said "Cyprus is appalled by today's indiscriminate
terrorist bomb attack against civilians in Jerusalem which
resulted in the loss of so many innocent lives."
</P>
<P>
"Such condemnable acts can never be justified to support any
cause", the ministry said, noting that these acts undermine the
objective of all the parties concerned and aim at putting in
jeopardy the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said it is confident that "this abhorrent
act will not deter the protagonists from their efforts to
reinvigorate the peace process in the Middle East and to surmount
the hurdles that were put on its way".
</P>
<P>
It expressed sympathy to the government and the people of
Israel, as well as profound grief to the families of the victims.
</P>
