<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Women Voice Their Demand for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
(by Yin Yongjian)
</P>
<P>
LUANDA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of women in the
war-plagued southern African country took to the street today
crying for their long-awaited peace.
</P>
<P>
Carrying placards inscribed with "We Want Peace, Not War",
"Stop Violence", "Build A Beautiful Future For Our Descendants"#,
these women marched to the national congress building of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Many of the demonstrators are women who have lost their
husbands or children in the two decades civil war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators walked to the front of the national
congress building where parliament members were having a meeting
and presented their letter for peace.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that the Angolan women who have suffered most
from the war in the country would sacrifice whatever they have
for a final peace, so that their younger generations would no
longer fight each other in the meaningless wars.
</P>
<P>
Analia Pereira, a woman parliament member said that "we, the
mothers who have suffered physically and spiritually in the wars
and lost our children should be safeguards for peace."
</P>
<P>
She said that "Angolan women should, joining hands with
Angolan men, strive for the final peace in the country, and never
allow the tragedy of war to befall on the land again."
</P>
<P>
The peace demonstration was organized to mark the African
Women's Day on July 31. Women in some other cities in the
war-ridden country also held similar activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-30 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lebanon Welcomes Lift of US Travel Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon welcomed U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright's decision to lift a 10-year-old ban on
U.S. citizens' travel to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri described the decision as
"positive," saying it indicated a "confidence in Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the lift of the travel ban is good, and we call on
U.S. businessmen, who want to invest in Lebanon, to come here and
they will be welcomed and will find new opportunities of
investment in this country," the premier said at a press
conference in his office.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the decision will "positively" affect
Lebanon's economy "since it will encourage Americans of Lebanese
origin to travel to Lebanon and encourage American businessmen,
investors and bankers to come back to Lebanon bringing with them
their families."
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese prime minister also underlined that Lebanon is
"against terrorism" and the Lebanese government will "cooperate
with all friendly countries in order to consolidate the security
in our state."
</P>
<P>
He added that "the lives and security of U.S. citizens will be
assured in Lebanon exactly the same as other nationalities as well
as the Lebanese." He noted that contacts are continuously
conducted between Washington and Beirut for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
The travel ban, imposed in 1987 by the U.S. State Department
following a series of kidnappings of U.S. citizens in Lebanon, has
been automatically renewed every six months.
</P>
<P>
Hariri announced that he was informed earlier today by Albright
of the "decision of the U.S. government and herself" to lift the
ban, one day before a deadline for either retaining or ending the
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Instead of the ban, Albright said, U.S. citizens "will be
warned (of dangers)" when they want to travel to Lebanon,
according to the Lebanese prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz said that his country
"welcomes the decision to lift the travel ban for which we have
not found any justifications in the recent years after the
re-establishment of stability and security in Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister was quoted by the state-run Lebanese
National News Agency as saying that the U.S. government's decision
will be "comprehensive" and will allow the Lebanese flag-carrier
Middle East Airlines (MEA) to resume flights to the U.S., and the
U.S. consul in Lebanon to issue entry visas.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Mohammed Salam, MEA's director general, noted that the
U.S. decision was a "very positive fruit of the efforts exerted by
the Lebanese government on the issue."
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. government "to complete this step with
other practical steps" which will facilitate the MEA to resume
direct flights between Lebanon and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Islamic fundamentalists in Lebanon were responsible for
abducting U.S. citizens and the U.S. has since demanded a Lebanese
government crackdown on Hezbollah, or Party of God, as a
precondition for lifting the ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
