<HEADLINE> UNDP to Focus on Nigeria's Agriculture, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) said today it will sharpen its focus on
agriculture and environmental issues in its fifth country program
of assistance in Nigeria from 1997 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
"Environment and natural resources management will be
implemented with agriculture in form of sustainable agriculture,
environment and rural development," a UNDP official said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ogo Okoro, UNDP's national program officer in
charge of environment, issues like conservation, agro-forestry
development, erosion and desertification, municipal waste
management and its conversion into organic fertilizer and
alternative sources of energy will be considered during the
period.
</P>
<P>
The program officer said that land degradation through sheet,
hydraulic and wind erosion, deforestation and pollution are the
major challenges to the country's environment.
</P>
<P>
Some international non-governmental organizations will be
invited to train Nigerians in participatory approaches, she said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth program, from 1992 to 1996, cost three million U.S.
Dollars and developed a blueprint for a national forestry action
plan in conjunction with the Federal Forestry Department and the
World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
