<HEADLINE> Lebanon Vows to Continue Resistance Against Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
today vowed that his country will continue military resistance
against Israel until Israeli occupation is eliminated in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remark while commenting on Washington's
decision to lift a ban on U.S. citizens' travel to Lebanon imposed
by U.S. State Department in 1987 following a series of kidnappings
of U.S. citizens in the country.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi was quoted by the state-run Lebanon Radio as saying that
his country "has been combating terrorism with all its strength."
</P>
<P>
The president regretted that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and others consider the existence of resistance against
Israel in south Lebanon as "dangerous."
</P>
<P>
He denied that those fighting the Israeli occupation are
terrorists. "Is that not a right for Lebanon to resist when its
land is occupied?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, accused by
Washington as a terrorist organization, spearheads a guerrilla
warfare in south Lebanon to oust the Israeli occupation forces out
of the occupied land.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi noted that the lift of the travel ban will not only
promote Lebanon's morale, but will also encourage all those who
want to come to Lebanon to see what has been happening since the
end of the 15-year civil war and what has been achieved in the
field of reconstructing infrastructures in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Albright informed Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri of the U.S. government's decision to lift the ban on
travel to Lebanon, a day before a deadline for either retaining or
ending the restrictions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
