<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Urges Restraint of North Ossetia, Ingushetia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin today urged
restraint of North Ossetia and Ingushetia over their worsening
tensions sparked by a series of clashes recently between ethnic
Ingush and North Ossetians, reported the Itar-Tass News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has ordered to draft a decree on priority measures for
normalizing the situation in the Prigorodny District, a disputed
area which used to belong to Ingushetia but now is under control
of North Ossetia, the Itar-Tass quoted Presidential Press
Secretary Sergey Yastrzhembsky as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is going to mediate between North Ossetian President
Akhsarbek Galazov and Ingush President Ruslan Aushev after he
returns to Moscow early next week from his holiday, Yastrzhembsky
said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between the two republics, which share a border in
southern Russia, escalated when some Ingush refugees were attacked
by North Ossetians Tuesday night in the Prigorodny District. The
attack was later halted by Russian interior troops.
</P>
<P>
Some Ingush territory, including the Prigorodny District, was
given to the Ossetians during the former Soviet time and many
Ingush were expelled from their home in 1944 to the Kazakh steppes.
</P>
<P>
They were allowed to return to their lands in the late 1950s
but Ossetians objected to their return.
</P>
<P>
Most ethnic Ingush are Muslims who speak a Caucasian language
while Ossetians are mostly Christians who speak an Iranian
language.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Zorin, chairman of the Duma Committee for the Affairs
of Nationalities today stressed that the conflict between the two
ethnic groups should be settled by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of the State Duma Mikhail Gutseriyev, who is in
charge of the work on a peaceful settlement of the Ossetian-Ingush
conflict, warned that the worsening of the situation may provoke
bloodshed similar to the one in 1992, when nearly 200 people were
killed in the fighting over the disputed Prigorodny District.
</P>
</TEXT>
