<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Nations Want Earlier Regional Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The seven South Asian countries
decided here today to speed up the realization of a South Asian
Free Trade Area (SAFTA).
</P>
<P>
Concluding their first meeting of the Inter-Governmental Group
(IGG) on Trade Liberalization at the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat, the seven member countries decided to hold two more
meetings this year to complete the deliberations in the third
round of trade negotiations by January 1998.
</P>
<P>
SAARC Secretary-General Naeem U. Hasan has said that the third
round was of crucial importance as it would put the South Asian
Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) on the fast track for
realizing the SAFTA by 2001, as decided in a May summit by members
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC),
which groups India, Nepal, Bhutan, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka
and the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, held at the SAARC Secretariat, marks the
beginning of the third round of trade negotiations among the SAARC
countries, said a press release issued by the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the seven countries conducted in-depth
multilateral and bilateral negotiations with a view to expanding
the list of products and deepening the tariff concessions on
products already covered under the SAPTA.
</P>
<P>
They reviewed the progress achieved so far in the
implementation of the SAPTA agreement.
</P>
<P>
They recommended that the studies on issues concerning SAFTA,
non-tariff barriers, discriminatory practices and trade imbalances
among the SAARC members should be completed quickly by the
Inter-Governmental Expert Group (IGEG) on Transition to SAFTA, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
They urged the IGEG to expedite formulation of an action plan
on SAFTA which would serve as a blueprint for successive rounds of
trade negotiations by the IGG.
</P>
<P>
The representatives agreed that it is necessary to provide
special and more favorable concessions to the least developed
member countries, namely Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal and the
Maldives.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that direct bilateral talks and frequent
exchange of visits should be organized to promote trade in the
region with a view to realizing the SAFTA by the targeted date.
</P>
<P>
The seven countries also decided to coordinate their approaches
on vital issues concerning trade and tariffs in the international
fora like the World Trade Organization and World Customs
Organization to effectively project and protect their collective
interests, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
