<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Leads Europe in Job Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Europe's slow economic growth and
underdeveloped service sector are proving to be major barriers to
European job growth, according to a noted economist in New York.
</P>
<P>
While the U.S. job machine continues to generate 2 to 3 million
jobs a year and reduce unemployment in a fast-growing labor force,
European employment growth is stagnant and the labor force has not
grown since 1991, said Gail D. Fosler, senior vice president and
chief economist of the Conference Board, whose analysis appeared
in a recent newsletter of the research group.
</P>
<P>
Her analysis challenges the widely-held thesis that vast
differences between the U.S. and European job markets are due to
the greater flexibility of the U.S. labor market, greater numbers
of small businesses in the U.S., and the creation of a large
number of low-wage jobs.
</P>
<P>
Fosler said that all three rationales are either "misstated or
misinterpreted." She noted, "The United States does have a
somewhat more flexible labor market than Europe, especially more
geographic mobility. But Europe has almost as much job creation
and job destruction as the U.S. and actually has more small
businesses than the U.S., even though they tend to be
micro-enterprises less well capitalized than those in the U.S."
</P>
<P>
She said that in the U.S., the pace of job growth in managerial
and professional specialty occupations, which includes computer
programmers, financial analysts, technicians and other high-tech
fields, is twice that in the lowest-wage occupations."
</P>
<P>
In addition, she said, the United States has many more
self-employed workers, while Europe actually has more small and
medium enterprises with salaried workers. The U.S. economy has 22
million small and medium enterprises, compared with 18 million in
Europe. Of these 22 million, 16.5 million are self-employed
workers with no employees -- more than 50 percent greater than the
number in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The economist also pointed to the gap of economic growth which
she said also led to job growth difference. "When an economy
doesn't grow, it is very hard for businesses to succeed," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
