<HEADLINE> Russia Won't Participate in Capturing War Crime Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Russian
Foreign Ministry said today that Russian troops in Bosnia will
never participate in missions aimed at capturing war crime
suspects in the area.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Tarasov, Director of the Press Bureau of the ministry,
said that Russia disapprove such missions because they are beside
the real objective of peace keeping of these troops.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov made the comments in the wake of a series of warnings
from international officials of a tough, new approach to nabbing
suspects in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, NATO's secretary-general Javier Solana pledged
that all war crime suspects will be behind bars before the
international community leaves Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov stressed that Russia believed that war criminals should
be punished, but that all related issues should be settled by
cooperation between all factions in Bosnia and the internation
tribunal under international laws.
</P>
<P>
He warned against actions that might worsen the trouble in the
area, and criticized the move by the British troops on suspects in
Bosnia early this month which triggered condemnation from the
local people.
</P>
<P>
Actions like this will not only escalate tension in the area,
but may also put into doubt the Bosnian local election scheduled
for September this year, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
