<HEADLINE> Cypriot Fisherman Sentenced for Transmitting AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A Greek Cypriot fisherman was
sentenced today to 15 months' imprisonment for knowingly
transmitting AIDS to his British lover.
</P>
<P>
Pavlos Georgiou, 40, from the southeastern coastal resort of
Ayia Napa, was charged under a 50-year-old British colonial law
enacted to check the spread of cholera and typhoid.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus gained independence from the British colonial rule in
1960. Under the law, the fisherman had faced a maximum sentence of
two years in jail, a fine of 1,500 Cyprus pounds (about 3,000
U.S. dollars), or both.
</P>
<P>
Georgiou was found guilty by court on Tuesday of not telling
Janette Pink, 45, from England, that he is HIV-positive during a
two-year love affair from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Georgiou's wife died of AIDS-related illness in 1994,
</P>
<P>
During the three-month trial, Georgiou had denied Pink's
accusation that he lied to her about having the disease and had
maintained that Pink was fully aware of his condition..
</P>
<P>
Pink, a mother of two, found out she was HIV-positive in
October, 1994, but stayed with Georgiou until July 1996 when she
developed full-blown AIDS.
</P>
<P>
She then returned to England for medical treatment and decided
to report Georgiou to the Cypriot authorities.
</P>
<P>
Legal analysts here said the jail sentence is "stiff" in view
of the health condition of Georgiou, who, as a father of four and
the sole support of his family, is dying of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Pink, on the other hand, is said to be in a "terrible"
condition.
</P>
<P>
Judge Antonis Liatsos said the sentence was passed as "a
deterrent because of the seriousness of the case and because the
courts have a duty to protect the health of the people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
