<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Launches New Debate on Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A new debate on France's immigration
policy is going on in the country following an earlier suggestion
by Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's Socialist government that two
tough immigration laws should be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
A committee in charge of re-writing the two laws, passed under
two former conservative governments, today presented a report to
Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The committee, consisting of 18 law experts and headed by
political scientist Patrick Weil, suggested that France mix
"pragmatism" with "humanity" when adopting a new immigration
policy.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "For a just and efficient policy of immigration,"
the report held that immigration itself is a positive thing and
that France was once a immigrants' country from 14th century until
1974, when it was attacked by economic recession and unemployment
worsening.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested that France give full nationality to all
the children born in the country from foreign parents, if they
have lived for years here before the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the government to ease restriction on visits and
stay in France by foreigners whose families live in France,
encourage foreign students and scholars to study and do research
in French colleges, provide asylum to "freedom fighters," stop
arresting and imprisoning foreigners who are found to be living in
secret places.
</P>
<P>
The report has brought about various responses from the
French society. Le Figaro said in a commentary today that the
geographical situation of France today is totally different from
that of the 19th century, when the country absorbed waves of
foreign immigrants from Poland, Italy, Belgium and Spain, and the
immigrant population have become a "substitution population"
living on the outskirts of the French society.
</P>
<P>
The paper Liberation said that the report's suggestion of easing
restriction on providing political asylum is intended to help the
Algerians who are at odds with both the government and Islamic
militants at home.
</P>
<P>
The National Front (FN) party of Jean-Marie Le Pen strongly
condemned the Weil report, while reiterating its call for closing
France's door to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"One should finish with the aberrations of the right of soil
and the folly of family reunion, one should reestablish the
controls at frontiers, denounce the Maastricht treaty, apply the
principle of national preference in employment, housing, and
family and social allowances," FN said in a communique released
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
