<HEADLINE> 200 Nations and Regions to Attend Athletics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- With a team from Iraq now
confirmed, a total of 200 countries and regions will take part in
the Sixth World Athletics Championships scheduled to open here
tomorrow night, making it the most well-attended sporting
competition in history.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 athletes from every corner of the globe will
compete in the sports festival from August 2 to 10 at the newly
built Olympic Stadium in the famous city, which is putting every
effort to win the world to back up its bid for holding the 2004
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The previous team entry record in history was set at the 1996
Olympic Games with 197 nations and regions, while the previous
championships best was 191 teams in 1995. The First World
Athletics Championships in 1983 drew 153 nations and regions.
</P>
<P>
The championships will open at the Panathinaikon Stadium, the
birth place of the modern Olympic movement 101 years ago. The
event will be the greatest sporting competition Greece has ever
known since the 1896 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The contest will be recounted by over 3,000 journalists from
the press, news agencies, radio and television. From the new
Olympic Stadium, the images of the events will be retransmitted to
over 200 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five years after its foundation, the International
Amateur Athletics Federation, the largest sports organization in
the world with 209 federations, is now holding its 41st congrass
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The first working session of the Congress ended last night has
decided to create new competition opportunities for teenagers.
The meeting agreed on a new initiative to try and capture the
attention of young people who may otherwise turn to other sports
and help national member federations in their efforts to recruit
new talent.
</P>
<P>
Council will first consider ways to give specdial assistance to
the IAAF Areas (Africa, Asia, Europe, Oceania, North America,
Central America and Caribbean, and South America) so they may
organise more competitions for this age group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
