<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fredericks Aims to Win a Sprint Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Frankie Fredericks of Namibia, who
romped two silver medals in both the 100 and 200 meters at last
year's Olympics, threw down his grautlet to his rivals by claiming
that he wants to take a sprint double triumph at the 6th World
Athletics Championships starting here tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
"My goal is to win the gold medals in the 100m and 200m
races. In such a great organisation you have to be totally
concentrated. I believe that I am in a very good form right now to
achieve my goal," said the 30-year-old sprinter here today.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks is one of the favourites to win the dash events in
the competition. His best time this year is 9.91 seconds in 100m,
and 19.90 in 200m. The year's leading sprinter is Ato Boldon of
Trinida who ran 9.89 and 19.77 seconds early this month.
</P>
<P>
Donovan Bailey of Canada, world and Olympic 100 meters
champion, ranks sixth on the year's list at 9.97 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Greene and Jon Drummond, both from the United States,
are also posing threats in the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
At the news conference here today, Bolton and Greene thought a
record between 9.78-9.79 will probably decide the gold medal in
the 100m at the championships. They said the weather conditions
ideal and quality of the track here especially favourable for an
unprecedented year in the 100m race.
</P>
<P>
"I feel physically and psychologically ready," said Ato, who
won two bronze medals at the Atlanta Olympics last year. "Besides
if I wasn't ready I wouldn't even have come to Athens. There is a
great difference between European meetings and a world class field
like the championships," added the 24-year-old.
</P>
<P>
Greene, who won the U.S. Championships at 9.90 and beat Bailey,
Boldon and Fredericks last month, said: "I feel obliged to do the
best possible thing for my country, and that will be no less than
the gold medal. I believe that I am in a great form and ready for
a world record."
</P>
<P>
The men's 100 meters final will be held on August 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
