<HEADLINE> "City of Generals" in East China's Shandong Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- People in the city of Rongcheng can
proudly count 57 local-born generals of new China tonight, the eve
of the 70th anniversary of the Chinese People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
Rongcheng, a revolutionary base during the War of Resistance
Against Japan (1937-1945) and the Liberation War (1946-1949), is
known as a hometown of war heroes and PLA soldiers.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years, more than 10,000 young people from the
city, located in east China's Shandong Province, have joined the
army, 80 percent of whom have received citations of merit.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-seven military officers from the city have achieved ranks
above major general, including one general, ten lieutenant
generals and 46 major generals of the navy, ground and air forces.
</P>
<P>
General Li Yaowen, the first general of Rongcheng and the
highest-ranking, had served as vice-minister of Foreign Affairs,
Chinese Ambassador in Tanzania and political commissar of the
Chinese navy.
</P>
<P>
To honor its outstanding natives, Rongcheng invested more than
five million yuan (about 602,000 US dollars) to build a large
commemorative tablet at the foot of Weide Mountain, which was
completed several days ago in preparation for the Army Day on
August 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
