<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: The Story of a Private Entrepreneur (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Millionaire entrepreneur Xu
Guanju credits his success in the chemical detergent business to
the use of science and advanced technology, an innovative
management style, and one special spoonful of salt.
</P>
<P>
Xu's rags to riches story begins with his life as a peasant in
Zhejiang Province, east China, and ends with his ownership of the Chuanhua
Group, regarded as the most influential privately-owned enterprise
in the province.
</P>
<P>
When Xu fell seriously ill at the age of 24, his family
couldn't handle the high medical costs. In a money-making scheme
to pay the bills, Xu's father gave his life savings of 2,000 yuan
(about 240 US dollars) to an experienced cook to develop a
powdered soup mixture which the two Xus planned to sell
door-to-door, traveling by tricycle.
</P>
<P>
The soup turned a profit and the Xus decided to work
independently, but the cook refused to part with his secret
recipe.
</P>
<P>
One day, young Xu saw him add a spoonful of white powder to the
soup to thicken the mixture. Xu hired a technician in Hangzhou to
analyze the soup and for 2,000 yuan learned the identity of the
mystery ingredient: ordinary table salt.
</P>
<P>
Xu says this high-priced folly led him to establish his own
chemical firm nine years later.
</P>
<P>
"I came to understand that I could get rich only by applying
science and technology in production," Xu said. "From then on, I
made up my mind to build my own business."
</P>
<P>
But this was a distant dream for Xu, who was in poor health,
had limited funds and only simple equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: The Story of a Private Entrepreneur  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under the guidance of some experts in organic chemistry, Xu set
up a workshop in his home and developed ten new products in
1988. That year he earned 150,000 yuan, which enabled him to pay
his debts and build a factory.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, he began to tackle the technical problems of removing
greasy dirt from fabric, and invented a detergent specially to
fight grime. The new product, called "901 Super Detergent," won a
gold medal at an international fair and netted a profit of over
one million yuan in 1991.
</P>
<P>
With his earnings, Xu expanded his firm and named it after his
father, Chuanhua.
</P>
<P>
The Chuanhua Group currently has technical and economic ties
with five countries and regions including the United States, Japan
and Germany. Twenty-one percent of Chuanhua's 500 employees are
college graduates; 20 of them hold leading management positions.
</P>
<P>
The group has developed scores of high-tech products, among
them the well-known "901 Super Detergent" that has made a profit
of over 10 million yuan since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The group's profits and taxes topped 21 million yuan in 1995.
Its annual sales volume is expected to top one billion yuan by
2000. And Xu has invested 70 million yuan to build a detergent
plant, the first phase of which is expected to be completed by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
To compete with other domestic and international companies, Xu
manages his company the modern way. Compared with the traditional
"iron bowl" system which secured life-long employment in some
Chinese enterprises, Xu initiated a "glass bowl" distribution
system, under which workers are paid according to the quality and
quantity of their work, and their wages are made public.
</P>
<P>
As a further incentive, any technician working for Chuanhua may
be rewarded for inventing a new product, and will receive a higher
bonus if the item is popular on the market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Mediation Panel Fails to Agree on Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A German mediation panel, comprising
parliamentary members from both the ruling and opposition parties,
failed today to agree on a tax reform package proposed by
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
The panel, however, agreed to abolish the business capital tax
in western Germany in 1997 and not to levy it in eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-99 tax reform plan was designed to boost Germany's
competitiveness as a business location, which would result in an
annual net tax-cut of 30 billion marks (17.6 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
It was forwarded to the mediation panel after being rejected by
the main opposition Social Democrats (SPD) in the SPD-dominated
Bundesrat, the upper house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The SPD had previously vowed to block the reform bill, calling
it socially unjust and lacking in solid financial basis. And Kohl,
deeming the bill as the best opportunity to boost investment and
jobs, had accused the Social Democrats of "treason" against the
over 4 million unemployed in Germany.
</P>
<P>
With the hope that a compromise deal could save the tax reform
bill, a major move of the government, Kohl had offered a series of
concessions to the SPD in a last-minute effort during
negotiations, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
The SPD had also thwarted Kohl's many other initiatives this
year. Today's results were seen as a major political setback for
Kohl, whose popularity, as opinion polls showed, went already
behind his possible SPD rivals in the elections scheduled for
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kohl has been German Chancellor since 1982 and is seeking a
fifth four-year term in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The government's failure in seeking a tax system overhaul
provoked fierce criticism from the business.
</P>
<P>
Wendelin Wiedeking, managing board chairman of Germany's luxury
carmaker Porsche AG, sharply attacked Kohl on Wednesday. "One must
not and cannot rule a state like this," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To me and many of my entrepreneurial colleagues, this
government has become very questionable," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on today's results, a German industry leader told
the press that it was "a serious setback for Germany as a venue
for industrial enterprises."
</P>
<P>
Germany's biggest companies are investing in countries where
taxes are lower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
