<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bronze Age Road Found In Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A wooden road thought to have been
built to allow farming on salt marshes 3,000 years ago has been
discovered on the bank of the Humber estuary in northern England,
the Daily Telegraph reported today.
</P>
<P>
Parts of the 20-yard long trackway have been so well preserved
by the mud that it provides significant clues to Bronze Age
woodworking techniques.
</P>
<P>
The find was made south of the village of Melton three weeks
ago by archaeologists from Hull University. The trackway is made
from branches woven into a "hurdle" and held in place by sharpened
wooden stakes.
</P>
<P>
Both its location, an area rich in Bronze Age remains, and the
axe marks on the wood suggest that it dates from around 1000 BC.
</P>
<P>
In the past, only one trackway of a similar age has been found
in northern England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
