<HEADLINE> Total Deposits, Loans Rise In Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Domestic credit grew at a rapid
pace in Hong Kong during the second quarter of 1997, the latest
official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA),
residential mortgage loans and other property-related lending
between April and June rose by 8.7 percent and 11.5 percent
respectively thanks to the buoyant property market.
</P>
<P>
Fueled by the active stock market, loans to stock brokers
jumped by 19.1 percent, while trade financing and lending to
wholesale and retail sectors increased by around six percent.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA also released the latest monetary statistics for the
month of June, when total loans and advances grew by 2.4 percent,
and total deposits rose by 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Deposits in Hong Kong dollars increased by 2.5 percent while
foreign currency deposits declined by 0.9 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
