<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Takes Measures to Regulate Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi government has newly
introduced measures to regulate the stock exchange in an effort to
stablize the country's financial conditions.
</P>
<P>
The measures concentrate on checking rogue speculators or
market forces in dealings, local newspaper Al-Zawraa said today.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry has banned all board directors and staff
members of the Baghdad Stock Exchange except the board chairman
and the director general of the exchange from making public
comments and statements on the market.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also barred disclosure of any information from the
Baghdad Stock Exchange authority regarding market matters like
changes in exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Finance Minister Hikmat El Azzawi, El Zawaraa reported
that foreign stocks would soon be allowed into the Baghdad Stock
Exchange for the first time since the exchange was established.
</P>
<P>
The financial documents dealt in at the Baghdad Stock Exchange
now are limited to treasury bonds, all securities issued by the
government or the socialist sector, and shares and stocks of of
Iraqi joint-stock companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
