<HEADLINE> HK Issues 100 Million New Coins to Cover Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary Authority
began to issue 100 million new coins from this week to make up the
shortfall of working coins.
</P>
<P>
The new coins have seven denominations, of which the 10 cents,
20 cents and 50 cents were initiated yesterday through 18 branches
of HongKongBank, while the other four denominations will be put
into circulation on August 1.
</P>
<P>
The new coins bear new designs which are different from the
existing coins with designs of the queen's head and the bauhinia.
The queen's-head coins are being retrieved by banks and will be
gradually out of circulation.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong to China aroused a rush for coins with
the head of Queen Elizabeth and many coins had gone into private
collections, resulting in a shortage of coins at banks and
retailers.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Monetary Authority said the new issues will
be sufficient to meet circulation demands.  
</P>
