<HEADLINE> Macao Security Problem Not Serious: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira
has said that Macao's security is not in a serious situation or
without control, a press release from the Government Information
Office said today.
</P>
<P>
The governor made the remark Wednesday following a shooting
incident at a hotel and an incendiary gadget attack on the garden
of the Government Palace in the morning.
</P>
<P>
"Although some criminal cases occurred recently, it is not
right to consider Macao a place unsafe or out of control," the
governor was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The shooting incident by three or four masked gunmen at about
2:00 (local time) Wednesday morning shocked Macao residents as a
sign of a new wave of triad fighting. Three people, a Filipino
security guard and two Portuguese engineers, were wounded in the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that Macao police are determined to crack
down on and stop organized crimes and that "citizens should remain
 calm."
</P>
<P>
"The shooting incident that happened in the morning might
happen anywhere in the world," he said. "I do not think Macao's
overall security is jeopardized."
</P>
<P>
But he urged local citizens to cooperate with the police and
offer them relevant information.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said Macao will also strengthen cooperation
with security organs in China's inland area, Hong Kong and the
Interpol in the fight against crimes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
