<HEADLINE> HK Film Industry Needs Creativity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's action-driven film
industry is in great danger and needs creativity, the head of the
new film and television school has said.
</P>
<P>
Dean Professor Richard Woolley said Hong Kong's film industry
is one of the world's biggest, but is in danger, the South China
Morning Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We want to help it prepare with creative ideas and skills when
 competition from Hollywood is so great," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said revolutionary changes had been introduced to degree
programs to give graduates a variety of career choices. The
courses stress a cooperative approach to the creative process.
</P>
<P>
The school offers 30 places in a diploma course, while more
than 250 students are competing for 24 degree places.
</P>
<P>
The report said figures show that local box office receipts
plummeted 27 percent last year, from 770 million HK dollars (98.72
 million US dollars) in 1995 to 560 million HK dollars (71.79
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Academy for Performing Arts' School of Film and
Television offers the first of its three-year degree and one-year
diploma programs in September. enditem
