<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Consolidate After Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market ended
July on a fractionally stronger note, consolidating following
Wednesday's long-awaited rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Shaw Stockbrokings' Jamie Spiteri said the Reserve Bank of
Australia's (RBA) fifth rate cut in a year had been well and truly
factored into the market in recent times.
</P>
<P>
"Now it's just a case of the market sitting back and trying to
assess where there is value in the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed just 0.1 points up at 2,735.1,
despite an 80.36 point rise to a new high of 8,254.89 on Wall
Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index added four points to 4,392.5.
</P>
<P>
The national bank Westpac rose 23.2 cents, or 2.73 percent, to
8.743 Australian dollars, with brokers suggesting it may have been
the beneficiary of some re-weighting in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank fell seven to 19.54 Australian
dollars, ANZ added three to 10.73 Australian dollars and CBA
slipped four to 16.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
All four major banks have now cut mortgage rates following the
RBA's easing, with Westpac emerging as the market leader in home
loan lending rates with a standard variable rate of 6.69 percent.
</P>
<P>
Entertainment and leisure concern Amalgamated Holdings was
sharply softer, shedding 20 cents to 6.90 Australian dollars
following news of a landslide in the Thredbo village where it owns
the resort.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said they expected the weakening to be temporary.
</P>
<P>
"Amalgamated is a very big company and Kosciuszko Thredbo is a
very little part of it," said David Perry, research director at
Austock Brokers.
</P>
<P>
News Crop gained two cents to 6.17 Australian dollars, its
preferred shares ended steady at 5.20 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index ended 3.7 points down at 1,443.9, with
BHP up 0.4 cents to 18.24 Australian dollars, Anglo-Australian
group Rio Tinto 2.3 cents lower at 20.877 Australian dollars and
mining giant WMC shedding 2.4 cents to 7.786 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 11.5 points lower at 1,325.9, with gold
bullion closing in Sydney at 326.50 US dollars an ounce, up from
326.05 US dollars in Sydney last.
</P>
<P>
Normandy eased five cents to 1.55 Australian dollars, while
Plutonic added 18 cents to 3.98 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 398.36 million shares valued at 1.025
billion Australian dollars (758.5 million US dollars) with falling
issues just outnumbering those rising by 504 to 501.  
</P>
</TEXT>
