<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Chad Urge Liberia to Foster Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Chad have urged
Liberia's President-Elect Charles Taylor to take urgent steps
toward achieving genuine national reconciliation in the
war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
In a communique after an unannounced one-day official visit
Wednesday by Chadian President Idriss Deby, the two countries
also stressed the need for all well-meaning Liberians to accept
the outcome of the July 19 polls so as to move the country
forward and put it in its rightful place in African and
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that the successful polls fully actualized the
Abuja Accord on Liberia, they called on the international
community to assist the new government in the country.
</P>
<P>
Taylor won a landslide victory in the election. He is
expected to be sworn in on the coming Saturday. Fifteen heads of
state including Nigeria's Sani Abacha, South Africa's Nelson
Mandela, Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe and Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic of Congo, are billed for the inauguration
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The west African peace-keeping force in Liberia has promised
to provide "an overwhelming security" for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
On recent developments in Sierra Leone, both Abacha and Deby
reaffirmed that the Abidjan Agreement which led to a cease-fire
would continue to serve as a viable framework for peace,
stability and reconciliation in that country.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that effective bilateral and regional economic
cooperation among African countries is required for continental
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, member states of the Organization of African
Unity should adopt necessary measures at national, regional and
continental levels to ensure effective implementation of the
Abuja treaty establishing the African economic community, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also expressed concern about present situation
in Congo's Brazzaville, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
