<HEADLINE> Oman's Bourse to Be Revamped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Oman plans to reorganize its
stock exchange, the Muscat Securities Market (MSM), with an
independent depository and settlement body and a separate
regulatory function to be established, a local newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"Reorganization of the market is high on the MSM's agenda,"
the daily Khaleej Times quoted Oman's Commerce and Industry
Minister Maqbool Bin Ali Bin Sultan as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the MSM's general assembly, delivered by
MSM executive president Mahmoud al Jarwani, the minister said a
new law had been prepared to make the market function more
professionally.
</P>
<P>
"The law provides for separation between the regulatory body
and the regulated entities - the trading floor and brokers," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said market capitalization rose 23 percent last
year to some 4.3 billion U.S. dollars. Twenty-one companies were
listed, one more than that of 1995, and all were oversubscribed.
</P>
<P>
He said primary market activity reflected business confidence,
good liquidity, low interest rates on bank deposits, the
saturation of investment in real estate and the relatively small
value of government bonds issued last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
