<HEADLINE> Uganda Protests Against Detention of Nationals in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has formally protested
against the "detention and harassment" of its nationals in Kenya
in the past two weeks when Kenyan police arrested more than 600
foreigners, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Minister of State for Foreign Affairs in charge of
Regional Cooperation Rebecca Kadaga Wednesday summoned Kenya's
High Commissioner Peter Ole Nkuraiyia and registered the protest,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Ugandans have been arrested and are being held
in various jails in Kenya, Kadaga said.
</P>
<P>
All attempts by Uganda's High Commissioner in Nairobi to have
them released "have been frustrated," she said, demanding the
Kenyan authorities establish the legal charges against the
detainees or set them free.
</P>
<P>
She also urged the Kenyan authorities to give Ugandan High
Commissioner to Kenya immediate access to those detained.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya is now holding the chairmanship of the East African
Cooperation. It is not proper that citizens from the Cooperation
countries should be treated like this," she charged.
</P>
<P>
However, Nkuraiyia said he has informed the Ugandan minister
that the recent events were "a normal security swoop we are
carrying out from time to time, not against Ugandans, Tanzanians
or Somalis."
</P>
<P>
He said Uganda may have over-reacted to the events, adding
that Nairobi has informed him that Ugandan High Commissioner has
not made a formal request to visit the detainees.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan authorities have no reason to deny the Ugandan High
Commissioner access to the detained persons, he noted.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 foreigners were reportedly netted in main cities
in Kenya in the last two weeks during a large-scale police
crackdown, which the police headquarters said was prompted by an
upsurge in car theft, murders, armed robberies and burglary.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has ordered police
to crack down on foreigners, saying foreign spies and criminals
masquerading as refugees have invaded the capital city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
