<HEADLINE> Israel Launches Sweeping Arrest Campaign in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli security forces
have arrested a total of 28 Palestinians in a sweeping campaign to
round up Hamas activists suspected of involvement in Wednesday's
Jerusalem suicide bombing, reported the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Army soldiers and plain clothes raided several Palestinian
villages to search for and pick up Hamas activists and their
families. All the arrests were carried out in villages still under
Israeli security control.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown is apparently part of the "security measures"
that the Ministerial Committee on National Security ordered
Wednesday night the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) and security
services to carry out against the Palestinian terrorist
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The arrests have taken place mainly in Jenin and Nablus,
cities in the northern part of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani disclosed
that the two suicide bombing attackers had still not been
identified. He confirmed that parts of their ID cards were found
in their bodies, but they may be forged.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview this morning, the minister said that
it was not yet clear which organizations the two terrorists
belonged to.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani said that police believe that the two were residents
of the West Bank, not from abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two explosive devices they carried may
come from the secret explosive lab in Bethlehem uncovered by
Palestinian police last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
