<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Pakistan Agree to Enhance Trade, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Pakistan today
agreed to enhance trade and investment cooperation through a
package of proposals, according to Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi.
</P>
<P>
The proposals involved the diversification of imports and
exports, joint ventures and the relocation of labor-intensive
industries, Abdullah said at the end of the inaugural three-day
Malaysia-Pakistan joint Commission meeting here which was
represented by Abdullah and his Pakistani counterpart Gohar Ayub
Khan respectively.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have also undertaken to look into the question of
our respective trade regimes with a view to facilitating greater
flow of trade between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to promote youth, sport, tourism
and cultural exchanges for closer cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Apart from trade and commodities, the meeting deliberated on
possible joint ventures in human resource development and
technical cooperation in science and technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the successful conclusion of the meeting would
chart a new direction in the bilateral relations between Malaysia
and Pakistan whose Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif began a three-day
official visit to Malaysia today.
</P>
<P>
Gohar said this was the first visit by Sharif to a Southeast
Asian country after assuming office in February this year
following his Pakistan Muslim League's victory in the general
elections, reflecting "the importance he attaches to Malaysia".
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was seeking to increase its exports of commodities
such as rice and fruits to Malaysia as the balance of trade was
now in Malaysia's favor, Gohar told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was also looking into Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad's suggestion that the two countries enhance their
collaboration in producing, processing and marketing palm oil.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the possibility of supplying defense equipment to
Malaysia, Gohar said Malaysian defense personnel could be trained
in Pakistani institutions.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that Malaysian investors establish joint
ventures or set up business in Pakistan including buying over
industries which were being denationalized or privatized.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade between the two countries is showing an upward
trend with total trade amounting to 698 million U.S. dollars last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
