<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Games Marketing Chief Resigned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Santiparb Tejavanija, marketing
chief of the 1998 Bangkok Asian Games in Bangkok, has resigned
after legal wrangling over a 10 million dollars sponsorship
agreement with a computer firm Acer Inc.
</P>
<P>
Santiparb Tejavanija sent his resignation late Wednesday to
Thai deputy Prime Minister Sukavich Rangsitpol who chairs the
government-run Bangkok Asian Games Organising Committee (BAGOC).
</P>
<P>
He has quit his seven BAGOC positions but will remain as
treasurer of the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA).
</P>
<P>
The computer firm is to develop a results service for the Games
from December 5 to December 20 next year.
</P>
<P>
But the final contract has taken more than a year to sign
because of haggling with lawyers at the Thai attorney general's
office, games sources said.
</P>
<P>
Games preparations have been dogged by personnel changes and
worries that venues and a new transportation system in the traffic
choked Thai capital would not be ready on time. The BAGOC
secretary general was forced to stand down by the government in
May.
</P>
<P>
But Swiss-based marketing company ISL has signed a record 82
million dollars worth of sponsorship and licensing deals for the
Games, indicating its growing importance in the sporting
calendar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
