<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Apologizes for Detention of Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today met two visiting Nigerian envoys, who were
briefly detained at a military air base Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Mandela as
saying that his meeting with Rabu Dagari and Mohammed Doba had
solved the "sensitive issue" between the two countries. But he
declined to divulge the details.
</P>
<P>
Reports of a diplomatic row between Nigeria and South Africa
surfaced earlier this week after Nigerian Information Minister
Walter Ofonagoro allegedly commented that Mandela was "the black
head of a white country".
</P>
<P>
Mandela said Ofonagoro had denied making the remark and he had
no reason to disbelieve him.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said relations between himself and Nigerian leader
Sani Abacha were, on a personal level, "cordial and harmonious".
</P>
<P>
Relations between South Africa and Nigeria were sound. There
had been some tension two years ago when Mandela called for the
suspension of Nigeria's membership of the Commonwealth after
Abacha ordered the execution of seven Nigerian human rights
activists.
</P>
<P>
Mandela today also revealed that the two Nigerian envoys were
mistakenly arrested and briefly detained at Wonderboom Air Base
outside Pretoria last night.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft carrying the Nigerian envoys was scheduled to
land at Johannesburg International Airport but instead touched
down at Wonderboom Air Base where Dagari and Doba were briefly
taken into custody, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
The president said he had apologized to the envoys and would
be sending a formal apology to Abacha. He also promised an
investigation into the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
