<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Fails to Agree on Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A mediation panel comprising
parliamentary members from both the ruling party and opposition
ended negotiations early today without agreement on a tax reform
package proposed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
The panel, however, agreed to abolish the business capital tax
in western Germany in 1997 and not to levy it in eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-99 tax reform plan was designed to boost Germany's
competitiveness as a business location, which would lead to an
annual net tax cut of 30 billion Deutsche marks (about 17.6
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It was forwarded to the mediation panel after being rejected by
the main opposition Social Democrats (SPD) in the Bundesrat, the
upper house of parliament, where the SPD holds the majority.
</P>
<P>
The SPD had vowed to block the reform bill, calling it socially
unjust and lacking in solid financial basis.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, deeming the bill as the best opportunity to boost
investment and jobs, had accused the Social Democrats of "treason"
against the over four million unemployed in Germany.
</P>
<P>
In hope of a compromise deal to save the tax reform bill, a
major move of the government, Kohl had offered a series of
concessions to the SPD in a last-minute effort during
negotiations, but in vain.
</P>
<P>
The SPD had also thwarted Kohl's many other initiatives this
year.
</P>
<P>
Today's results were seen as a major political setback for
Kohl, whose popularity, as opinion polls have showed, goes already
behind his possible SPD rivals in the elections scheduled for
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kohl has been the German Chancellor since 1982 and is seeking a
fifth four-year term in the upcoming elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
