<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 100 MPs Condemn Arrests of Aides to Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 leftist and liberal
parliamentary deputies have condemned the recent arrests of seven
high-ranking officials of Tehran's municipality on charges of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
In their letter to Iran's Judicial Chief Mohammad Yazdi, which
was published by the Persian daily Iran today, the members of the
Parliament criticized the judicial branch for "political
motivations behind the recent arrests."
</P>
<P>
"The unfair,... and illegal treatment (arrests) which were
accompanied by sensational propaganda created the impression that
perhaps political motivation has overshadowed other
responsibilities of the Justice Ministry officials in Greater
Tehran," the letter signed by more than 100 deputies of the
270-seat Parliament said.
</P>
<P>
Plain-cloth men from the Justice Ministry raided the Mayoral
Office in downtown Tehran Monday and Tuesday and arrested seven
top aides on charges of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
In a show of support for Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein
Karbaschi, whose group has been the target of the recent
arrests, the deputies touched on many accomplishments the mayor
has made during his eight-year tenure and called his role as
instrumental in the construction era headed by outgoing President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Once a leftist, Karbaschi has switched camps in the past
decade, serving as one of the most outspoken champions of
liberal causes in the Islamic Iran.
</P>
<P>
He has played a pivotal role in the formation of liberal
group known as G-6 that has supported the development policies
of Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi and his group fully backed the presidential bid of
Mohammad Khatami who won a landslide victory by defeating his
main rival -- hardliner Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar
Nateq-Nouri, who is backed by Iranian Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei has launched the nationwide anti-corruption campaign
early this month and his close aide Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati has
called for sweeping judicial measures to bring corruptive
governmental officials to justice.
</P>
<P>
On July 20, Judicial Chief Mohammad Yazdi announced that he
will set up a special court to deal with rampant governmental
corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 64-year-old president, his family members and some
cabinet members have been under constant attacks by hardliners
for various kinds of corruption since the beginning of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 156 members of the 270-seat Parliament called on July 1
for an investigation into the assets of top officials of the
Rafsanjani administration and their families.
</P>
<P>
The latest anti-corruption campaign comes at the end of the
Rafsanjani administration's second and last term. Rafsanjani will
officially step down from office on August 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
