<HEADLINE> Haikou Cross-Straits Seminar Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A three-day seminar on relations
across the Taiwan Straits ended today in Danzhou, Hainan Province,
with participants offering suggestions on how to increase
economic and agricultural exchanges and trade.
</P>
<P>
The seminar attracted some 100-odd scholars and experts from
the Chinese mainland, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macao, Japan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Discussions centered on economic ties and trade, agricultural
cooperation, and other exchanges across the Taiwan Straits, as
well as the influence China's resumption of excercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong will have on cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
Participants tabled specific suggestions concerning the
aforementioned areas and reached a consensus on wide-ranging
issues.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the historical trend towards the rapid
development of economic ties and trade across the Taiwan Straits
will promote the growth of mutually supplementary economies.
</P>
<P>
Participants also pointed to the great potential for
agricultural exchanges and cooperation across the Taiwan
Straits. They stressed the imperativeness of adopting more
specific and effective methods to accelerate cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Other discussions concerned issues related to using the
favorable situation following Hong Kong's return to the motherland
to accelerate the development of relations across the Taiwan
Straits by using the favorable situation of Hong Kong's return to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and foreign scholars expressed optimism concerning
the future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly sponsored by the Taiwan Studies
Society, the All-China Federation of Taiwan Compatriots and the
Taiwan Research Institute under the China Academy of Social
Science. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
