<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Communists Win Landslide Victory in District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) has, as expected, won a
landslide victory in the district development committee (DDC)
elections held on July 19, while the main opposition Nepali
Congress (NC) has secured the majority only in one district.
</P>
<P>
Of the 54 DDCs where the results have been declared by the
Election Commission, the CPN-UML has formed 41 DDCs on its own
strength.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, it has won chairmanship in 44 districts,
vice-chairmanship in 40 districts and 471 members.
</P>
<P>
While the NC has bagged six chairmanships, four
vice-chairmanships and 96 members. It won the majority only in
Manang district.
</P>
<P>
The ruling National Democratic Party (RPP) has secured three
chairmanships, eight vice-chairmanships and 68 members.
</P>
<P>
The outcomes for Syangja and Baglung districts are yet to be
declared.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the DDC elections, the Supreme Court ordered
postponement of elections in Arghakhanchi, Gorkha, Ilam and Parsa
districts on the ground of incompletion in the village development
committee (VDC) elections.
</P>
<P>
DDC elections in the remaining 15 districts in the mid-western
development region, where ultra-leftist violence stalled the local
polls in May, are slated for later this year.
</P>
<P>
The DDC elections are the third and final phase of the local
polls in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Elections in 3,192 VDCs and 58 municipalities took place on May
17 and May 26 respectively, in which the CPN-UML bagged about 53
percent of the seats contested.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
