<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Court To Handle Tourist Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- If tourists visiting the Three
Little Gorges, a famous scenic spot in Chongqing in southwest
China, encounter any difficulties, they can turn to China's first
tourist court for help in resolving the problem.
</P>
<P>
There has been a tourism boom in the area in recent years, but
along with it has come some problems caused by unscrupulous
tourist agencies, resulting in disputes between them and tourists.
</P>
<P>
So, on February 16, 1995, the local authorities established the
first court specializing in travel disputes, which often include
over charging, violation of contract, and other forms of
unfairness. Compensation for those who win their claims can run
from 10 yuan (a little more than one dollar) to 5,000 yuan, and
disputes must be resolved in two or three days.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the court work from 5 a.m. to 8 p.m. during the
busy season," said the president of the court. And for
convenience' sake, the court accepts complaints over the phone and
through the mail.
</P>
<P>
One example was Deng Yanbing, a tourist from Xi'an, who on
April, 26, 1995 was overcharged 20 yuan for a boat ride. Thirty
minutes after Deng telephoned the court, he and other tourists got
compensation from the boat's owner.
</P>
<P>
The court has already handled more than 60 cases, and has
answered over 5,000 legal inquiries. The number of complaints are
down this year, however, with only five reported between January
and May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
