<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Tibetan Philanthropist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Six new primary schools will open in
September in Nanmulin County, the Tibet Autonomous Region, thanks
to the efforts of Zhaxi Cering, a 68-year-old Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to do something for the children in my
hometown," said Cering.
</P>
<P>
The philanthropic Cering had used well over 770,000 yuan
(96,000 US dollars) by the end of last year to build 30 primary schools in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The schools have provided over 2,200 children in 54 villages
with an education, and enrollments in recipient counties have
jumped dramatically from 37 percent in 1990 to 67.9 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Cering returned to China in 1964 after completing his studies
in India and the United States. Cering, 34 at the time, then
entered the Tibet Nationalities Institute to study Chinese.
</P>
<P>
He accepted a position as an English teacher at Tibet
University in 1982 and has since devoted his time to
education. Cering won praise in 1988 for his compilation and
publication of the first English-Tibetan-Chinese Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
Cering earned some 10,000 yuan from an English school he opened
to train the first group of young Tibetan tourist guides.
</P>
<P>
"The money I earned from the school was a considerable sum when
considering that I previously couldn't afford a bicycle," said
Cering. "At the same time, however, I was deeply concerned about
dropouts in poverty-stricken areas."
</P>
<P>
Cering followed-up on his concern by approaching a related
county department and expressing his desire to build schools. His
first primary school opened in Guque Village in 1991 has an
enrollment of 48 students.
</P>
<P>
Upon his retirement, Cering entered business. He explained, "I
need money to realize my wish of building schools." He took full
advantage of opportunities created while marketing Tibetan
handicrafts both at home and abroad to inform clients of his
ambition to build schools for poverty-stricken children. Cering's
efforts were rewarded with substantial donations for related
projects.
</P>
<P>
"It would have been impossible to build so many schools without
help from friends," said Cering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Deported From Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 30 Ugandans have been
deported from neighbouring Kenya since Monday, local newspaper
"The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
All Ugandans were back without Kenya police escort except
eight handed over Wednesday, border official said.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan policemen escorting the Ugandans claimed the deported
had caused insecurity and other forms of lawlessness in Kenyan
villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
Rebecca Kadaga, Ugandan Minister of State for Foreign Affairs,
Wednesday sommoned Ole Ukurayiro, Kenyan High Commissioner in
Kampala, and lodged a protest against Kenya's "detention and
harassment" of Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 Ugandans had been arrested and were being held
in various jails in Kenya, with some being held for more than two
weeks, said Kadaga, adding all attempts by Uganda's High
Commissioner in Nairobi to have them released "have been
frustrated".
</P>
<P>
The minister demanded that the Kenyan authorities establish
the legal charges against the detainees or set them free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
