<HEADLINE> Discussions on Congolese Crisis Reaches Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Talks on the Congolese crisis
held in the Gabonese capital Libreville reached deadlock again
following disagreement between Congolese President Pascal
Lissouba and his rival former President Sassou Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said Sassou rejected the draft
plan discussed during peace talks in Libreville last Saturday,
saying only a transition period led by a public salvation
government could establish peace in the Republic of Congo (B).
</P>
<P>
Lissouba's party, the Pan African Union for Social Democracy
responded to the announcement by rejecting the idea of the
transition period, noting that to accept a transition period is
to question all democratic institutes as well as the constitution
itself.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, Sassou is completely against the
prolongation of President Lissouba's mandate, adding that keeping
Lissouba in power threatens peace and security in the country.
</P>
<P>
Lissouba's mandate has already been extended by the Congo's
Constitutional Council on July 21. The council delayed the
elections initially set for July 27 and declared that Lissouba
should stay on beyond August 31 when his mandate was to expire
until a successor was elected. However, no new date for elections
was set.
</P>
<P>
Forces loyal to President Lissouba and the militia of former
President Sassou Nguesso have been fighting since June 5 when the
government soldiers tried to disarm Sassou's militia. More than
2,000 people have been killed during the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire which has been in effect since July 13 is
respected by the both sides. Congolese capital Brazzaville
remains calm today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
