<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Views on Science Fiction (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A great many Chinese people view
science fiction as children's literature, with one recent article
noting that "science fiction and fairy tales are both far from
real life."
</P>
<P>
Chinese sci-fi writer Xing He does not see it that way.
</P>
<P>
"For thousands of years, Chinese have been used to seeking
answers in history, and held that the ancient ideas are the
best. In the traditional Chinese concept, exploring the future is
useless," Xing said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, China's modernization drive requires the
creativity and daring that science fiction embodies.
</P>
<P>
A group of delegates attending the ongoing '97 Beijing
International Conference on Science Fiction share the opinion that
the science fiction craze that swept the country since the late
1970s was attributed to China's reform and opening-up drive, as
well as the global technological revolution.
</P>
<P>
From then on, Chinese began to view their country differently,
believing that a future marked by change was possible.
</P>
<P>
"Science fiction has become a literature form closer to real
life," said Pan Jiazheng, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of
Engineering, who is also a sci-fi writer. His works highlight the
important role of hi-tech in solving China's major problems, such
as birth control and desertification.
</P>
<P>
"Since ancient times, the Chinese have liked fantasy stories,
but their illusions lack scientific proof," said Jin Tao, director
of Popular Science Press.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese created the legend of people flying to the moon
long before the world famous sci-fi writer Jules Verne popularized
the idea in his novels. According to one Chinese tale, Chang'e
flew to the moon by swallowing a powerful elixir stolen from her
husband.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
