<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A five-state panel overseeing the implementation of
cease-fire in the border area between Lebanon and Israel urged the
fighting sides to strictly comply with a truce agreement reached
last year. Representatives from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and
the United States, who make up of the cease-fire monitoring
committee, attended the 19-hour meeting on Thursday morning in the
headquarters of the U.N. peacekeeping forces at the south
Lebanese border town of Naqoura.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government has decided to break off
negotiations, the state-run Israel Radio reported on Thursday
morning. The government also decided to allow Israeli security
forces to enter the Palestinian self-rule areas to carry out
missions, taking no notice of Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- About 15,000 people was told Wednesday to be ready to
abandon their homes at a moment's notice after the swollen Oder
River on the German-Polish border threatened to flood a vast
low-lying area of eastern Germany. Some 4,000 troops who had been
fighting a losing battle overnight to save the weakening dikes in
the northern part of the Oder were forced to retreat from the
riverside when a 50-meter-long stretch of dike was torn open by
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Former U.S. peace mediator on Bosnia Richard
Holbrooke will visit the Balkans next week as part of a U.S. team
that will press for implementation of the Dayton peace accords,
the State Department announced Wednesday. He will join a U.S. team
led by Robert Gelbard, U.S. special representative for Dayton
implementation, and would visit Bosnia, Serbia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Wednesday that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has assured her to
commit himself to "restore a secure atmosphere" after two bombings
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan Wednesday condemned the two suicide bombings in
the West Jerusalem, which killed 14 people and wounded over 170
others, as "terrorist" acts against the innocent people, Radio
Jordan reported. The extremists committed the crime as hopeful
signs just emerged for the resumption of the Middle East peace
process, said a Jordanian government spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
