<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Wall Materials Being Promoted In South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangdong Province is
drafting long-term plans for promoting the development of new wall
materials to increase their use.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, bricks made from local soil have been popular in
rural China, resulting in the destruction of a large amount of
farmland. The province hopes that new wall materials will account
for 25 percent of the wall materials output there by the year
2000, and 40 percent by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
New wall materials are made of organic materials and are widely
used elsewhere in the world. Chinese experts say that using them
is an effective way to protect farmland, save energy, and improve
labor efficiency.
</P>
<P>
From 1991-95, Guangdong produced more than 20 kinds of new wall
materials, with an output equivalent to six billion standard
bricks. In 1995, it was able to save 192,000 tons of standard
coal, and recycled 200,000 tons of discarded materials, preventing
270 hectares of farmland from being destroyed.
</P>
<P>
New wall materials now appear in 20 percent of the buildings
in Guangzhou and 35 percent in Shenzhen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
