<HEADLINE> Five Outlawed Members Arrested in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Five members of an outlawed
opposition group have been arrested in Iran and charged with
espionage activities during presidential election campaigns in
May, a press report said today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Kar-o-Karegar reported that the group known
as Mojahedin Khalq Organization (MKO) is based in Iraq and has
waged arm struggle against Tehran government for the past 16
years. MKO leader Massoud Rajavi is supported by the Iraqi
government, the newspaper alleged.
</P>
<P>
"Three members of the MKO team were arrested in (Iran's
southern province of) Kerman and the other two were arrested at
the border regions while trying to exit Iran illegally," an
unnamed information ministry official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not mention when they were arrested or
who they are.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the agents of his ministry searched the
houses belonging to this group and acquired intra-organizational
documents of the group.
</P>
<P>
"Members of this team have had such activities as espionage
during the presidential election, identifying sensitive security
areas, writing slogans on the walls and distributing tracks," he
added.
</P>
<P>
During the presidential election campaign which ended in May 23
landslide victory for Mohammad Khatami, Iranian authorities
arrested a number of MKO operatives who had infiltrated into Iran.
</P>
<P>
The operatives, the government said, had been sent into Iran
to initiate a campaign of terror and to disrupt presidential
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
