<HEADLINE> Monitors Call for Commitments to Cease-Fire in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A five-state panel overseeing
the implementation of cease-fire in the border area between
Lebanon and Israel urged the fighting sides to strictly comply
with a truce agreement reached last year.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the
United States, who make up of the cease-fire monitoring
committee, ended a 19-hour meeting this morning in the
headquarters of the U.N. peacekeeping forces at the south
Lebanese border town of Naqoura.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which was set up under the cease-fire
understanding mediated in April, 1996, by the U.S. and
France between Lebanon and Israel, held the meeting to discuss
one complaint lodged with it by Lebanon and three by Israel
over cease-fire violations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the end of the meeting, the 15th of
this year, the committee accepted as "fatal" what the Lebanese
side said in its complaint that three mortar shells fired by
Israeli forces or the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army (SLA)
militia landed in Habboush Monday, "causing damages of properties
in the town."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegates argued that the incident was the
result of a "defensive response" to an attack launched by
Lebanese armed groups from Habboush, the committee statement
said.
</P>
<P>
In its own complaints, Israel accused Lebanese resistance
fighters of violating the so-called "April understanding" by
attacking civilian areas in the Israeli self-proclaimed "security
zone" at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring team said it also accepted as fatal that at
least one Katyusha rocket fired by Lebanese armed groups landed
near Kawkaba over Saturday night and mortar shells landed in
Rihan Sunday, leading to the wounding of a woman.
</P>
<P>
However, just as what it had done in its previous
meetings, the committee refrained from condemning any side for
breaches of the cease-fire understanding, which demands civilians
on both sides of the border to be neutralized from military
operations.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring committee meeting was held amid reports of
trading fire between Muslim guerrillas of the Lebanese
pro-Iranian Hezbollah on the one hand, and Israeli forces and
their client Lebanese militia on the other in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Lebanese army units have cleared
the last land mines from the road leading to a crossing
between the south Lebanese port city of Saida and Jezzine, a
mainly Christian-populated town at the tip of the
Israeli-occupied border strip.
</P>
<P>
Although the government hopes to open the Kfar Falous
crossing Friday to allow a free access to Jezzine, there is
no indication that the SLA has begun clearing its section of
the road east of Kfar Falous, the Lebanese English daily the
Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Antoine Lahd, commander of the 2,500-strong SLA militia had
announced its agreement to the reopening last week.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted army sources as saying that the
Lebanese army units in the area were placed on full alert
to put into effect the government's decision to reopen the
crossing as scheduled Friday, which coincides with Lebanon's
Army Day.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the section of the road to be manned by
the Lebanese troops seemed ready for traffic after soldiers
finished removing mines and earth mounds.
</P>
<P>
But land mines in the fields on either side of the road
are left to remain there to block possible infiltration by
SLA militiamen, the army sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
