<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Quality Control on Ginseng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China is working out a national
standard for the quality classification of American ginseng
products to upgrade the quality of both domestically-made and
imported American ginseng.
</P>
<P>
The standards, complete and authoritative, will be the first of
the kind in the world, said one of the experts who is formulating
the standards.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Li Shudian from Jilin Agricultural University said the
standards will help safeguard consumers' interests, promote the
healthy growth of China's own American ginseng industry, and
tighten the control on the import of low-quality ginseng.
</P>
<P>
The regulations cover five types of ginseng: American ginseng,
activated American ginseng, American ginseng slices, chewing
tablets of American ginseng and bagged American ginseng tea.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more Chinese have begun to use American, or
western ginseng, for health purposes, and large quantities of
ginseng have been imported from the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
China introduced the technique for growing the plant in 1980,
and developed its own American ginseng industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, the Ministry of Health announced that the quality of
China-made American ginseng was already on a par with that of the
imported kind, and listed it in the Chinese pharmacopoeia.
</P>
<P>
With a total cultivating area of more than 3.5 million square
meters and an annual output of 100 to 150 tons of ginseng
products, China is now the third largest American ginseng
producer, following Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Jilin Agriculture University, Shanghai Herbal
Medicine Co. Ltd and Beijing First American Development Center
have been working on the draft of the standards for the quality
classification of American ginseng since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The standards are expected to be announced by the end of this
year, according to Prof. Li. 
</P>
</TEXT>
