<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hopes Fading For 20 Trapped Under Ski Lodge Rubble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Hopes were fading for 20 people
trapped under the rubble of two collapsed ski lodges at a resort
town in southeast Australia, as the rescue mission may take days,
police said today.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen hours after the massive landslide brought down part of
the hillside at Thredbo, a resort town in New South Wales state
some 150 kilometers southwest of Canberra, police said there was
still no sign of survivors and the cold would not help their
chances.
</P>
<P>
Chief Superintendent Bruce Johnston was quoted by the
Australian Associated Press as saying that most of the people
trapped by the landslide, which occurred just before midnight last
night, were aged between 25 and 50 and were workers at the ski
village.
</P>
<P>
Some were from overseas, including those from the United
States, Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
Most might be sleeping when a chunk of cliff above Alpine Way
slipped, pushing Carinya Lodge 100 meters down the slope on to the
Bimbadeen staff lodge.
</P>
<P>
One person was believed to be inside Carinya Lodge, while
Bimbadeen was home to between 18 and 20 senior staff.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 emergency workers were at the scene shoring up
the edges around the slide, and navy and police helicopters were
flown in.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers used flexible fiber optic cameras to search for
survivors in areas deemed stable.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a sweep of the rubble using sensitive sound equipment
failed to detect any signs of life.
</P>
<P>
A geophysicist flown in by the police from Sydney this morning
to assess the scene had warned there was likely more slippage some
time today, Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
The victims might not be reached for several days, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The longer it goes obviously their chances are diminishing,
everyone's different," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly the chance of survival is going to be minimized but we
have to be careful, it may well be that something we do could
(cause) further slippage, we may indeed take a life that may be
saved in a day or so," the police officer said.
</P>
<P>
Police felt helpless and shocked by the situation, which they
described as "horrendous."
</P>
<P>
It was still not known what triggered the landslide, but it was
believed water seeping from the mountain might have weakened the
soil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
