<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Under-Funded Tourism Leads to Billions of Rand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is losing
billions of Rand annually in foreign exchange earnings because
of an under-funded tourism industry, said the South African
Tourism Board (SATOUR) chairwoman Liz Westby-Nunn.
</P>
<P>
Westby-Nunn said that tourism could be one of the big four
foreign exchange earners alongside manufacturing, mining and
agriculture, a local daily Sowetan reported today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that 1.2 million foreigners visiting South
Africa last year spent about 12.5 billion Rand (about 2.7 billion
US Dollar). This year's numbers, in spite of the underfunding
problem were likely to increase.
</P>
<P>
Westby-Nunn said tourism was South Africa's only industry with
an assured and sustainable growth potential, where significant
new employment could be created.
</P>
<P>
Citing tourism contributed 4.5 percent to Gross Domestic
Product, she said the government's 63 million Rand (about 14
million US Dollar) funding to the SATOUR the current financial
year was under-funded.
</P>
<P>
The government had to appreciate the status of tourism not
only as a foreign exchange earner, but as contributor to the
country's economy as well, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the South African government was
considering imposing a tourism levy in a bid to improve the
under-funded tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
