<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Reform Health Care System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has decided to set up
medics commissions in September to carry out health care reforms
aimed at to streamlining hospitals and clinics.
</P>
<P>
The commissions, proposed by Health Minister Peter Boyadjiev,
will submit a list of district and university hospitals which will
remain operational.
</P>
<P>
Some hospitals will possibly be closed down while new wards
start operating to meet region-specific needs, said Boyadjiev.
</P>
<P>
The commissions will decide the number of the medics, the
budget of individual health care establishments and the needs for
medicines in accordance with the predominant diseases and the age
composition of the local population.
</P>
<P>
The future of a hospital will depend on several criteria,
including the total number of in-patients, patients' average age,
diseases of highest incidence and transport links with the nearest
health care establishment.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian health care system has been in operation for 50
years in a centralized principle. Now 70 percent of health care
establishments are funded by the municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The public purse will continue to finance the sector till the
launch of a medical insurance system which is unlikely in the
coming two years.
</P>
<P>
Four health-related bills are expected to be introduced at
parliament by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
