<HEADLINE> Uganda to Send Additional 3,000 Troops to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will send additional 3,000
troops to fight rebels in western Uganda, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni Wednesday told a rally in western
Kasese District that Uganda and the Democratic Republic of Congo
(formerly Zaire) planned to join hands in fighting against the
Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) rebels, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
ADF is a rebel group operating in Rwenzori Mountain connecting
the Democratic Republic of Congo and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni pledged Tuesday to eliminate ADF rebels.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question concerning the government's stand on the
return of a local traditional leader Prince Charles Wisley
Iremangoma, Museveni said he will not oppose to his return, but
the prince should not use violence to grab power.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's constitution recognizes traditional leaders as
monarchs.
</P>
<P>
ADF rebels want to use the return of the prince as a
propaganda weapon against the government.
</P>
<P>
If Iremangoma is involved in the ADF rebellion, he will face
the laws, the president warned.
</P>
<P>
Iremangoma left Uganda to study in the United States in 1984
and has kept a low profile regarding ADF allegations that they
are fighting to meet him as king in the region of Rwenzori
Mountain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
