<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Economy Grows amid Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Polish economy continued to grow
in the first six months of the year despite an increase in trade
deficit and a drop in agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Figures released today by the Central Statistics Bureau showed
that in the period under review, gross domestic product (GDP)
increased 7.8 percent, up from 7.1 percent in the second half
of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, GDP went up by 8.2 percent over the same
period of last year, a record high since the start of economic
transition in 1989.
</P>
<P>
But because of the flooding which hit 25 provinces in southwest
Poland, the GDP is estimated to grow 4.6 percent in the second
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimate that the GDP growth rate for the whole year
may be 6 percent, higher than the targeted 5.5 percent but lower
than last year's 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, industrial output continued to grow at
a pace quicker than that of the corresponding period of last year
with the second quarter industrial output increasing 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Polish economists said that the economic "overheating" which
began in the later half of last year has not yet cooled down,
hindering further development.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, trade deficit amounted to 12.7 billion U.S. dollars,
or 3 percent of the GDP. In the first five months of this year,
exports increased by 6.6 percent while imports soared by 23.4
percent, leading to an additional trade deficit of 4 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that trade deficit of the whole year may amount
to 17.3 billion dollars, accounting for approximately 5.5 percent
of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Adverse weather conditions have resulted in a lean year of
agriculture. Grain output has reduced by about 1 million tons,
making it difficult to curb price hikes. From January to June,
prices increased 16.1 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, citizens in Warsaw, Krakow, Katowice and other
major cities fell prey to price rise. The prices for meat and
vegetables jumped from 30 to 50 percent, making it impossible to
bring inflation down to the planned 13 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, the financial situation worsened
with a rise in production costs and a drop in profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0175 </DOCNO>
