<HEADLINE> Israel Suspends Talks With PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government has
decided to break off negotiations until the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) smashes the terrorist infrastructure in its mist,
reported the state-run Israel Radio this morning.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to allow Israeli security forces
to enter the Palestinian self-rule areas to carry out security
missions taking no notice of Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's spokesman Shai
Bazak said that the negotiations, due to resume this week, would
remain in abeyance.
</P>
<P>
Bazak's statement came followed a late-night cabinet security
session debating on the serious situation in the wake of the
twin suicide bombing attack that took place in Jerusalem's
central open market Wednesday afternoon. A total of 13 Israelis
were killed and 168 wounded.
</P>
<P>
According to a four-point cabinet communique faxed to Xinhua
early this morning, the Ministerial Committee on National
Security decided on a number of steps in the wake of the
terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
The communique said: "The committee directed the Israel
Defense Forces (IDF) and the security services to carry out a
series of security measures against the Palestinian terrorist
organizations."
</P>
<P>
"The Ministerial Committee on National Security views the
Palestinian National Authority as responsible for the acts of
terrorism and murder against innocent civilians in Jerusalem
since it did not take the steps which it was committed to
taking, including war on the terrorist organizations and their
infrastructure," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The Ministerial Committee also demands that the PNA honor all
of its commitments to fight terrorist organizations and their
infrastructure, and prevent violence and incitement to violence,
said the communique.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Ministerial Committee determines that in
order for it to be possible to advance the peace process, the PNA
must honor all of its commitments, including -- first and
foremost -- to fight the terrorist organizations and their
infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
