<HEADLINE> Chang, Ivanisevic Advance at du Maurier Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Michael Chang romped, Goran
Ivanisevic struggled and Thomas Muster survived as the top seeds
advanced at the du Maurier Open tennis championships in Montreal
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chang, the top seed, led 6-1, 1-0 when his rival, Sandon Stolle
from Australia, quitted with a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
Stolle, son of former French and U.S Open champion Fred Stolle,
injured his shoulder Tuesday night while beating crowd favorite
and top-ranked Canadian Sebastien Lareau.
</P>
<P>
The second seed, Ivanisevic, wasted five match points in the
middle set of a 6-3, 6-7 (8-10), 6-4 victory over Brett Steven of
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The third-seeded Muster showed he was also competitive on
hardcourts with a tough three-set victory over American qualifier
Jeff Salzenstein.
</P>
<P>
Seventh-seeded Mark Philippousis of Australia downed American
qualifier Steve Campbell 6-2, 6-4, while No. 5 Thomas Enqvist of
Sweden won a 6-7, 6-4, 6-4 battle over 19-year-old German Tommy
Haas.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Rafter, seeded 11th, was the only seed upset on
Wednesday, losing in three sets to fellow Australian Michael
Tebbutt.
</P>
<P>
Chang next will meet American Alex O'Brien, who beat Marcus
Ondruske of South Africa. Ivanisevic will take on American Jeff
Woodruff and the Muster will play France's Fabrice Santoro.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Wayne Ferreira, the 13th seed who won the du
Maurier last year in Toronto, beat Italian qualifier Cristiano
Caratti 6-1, 6-2 and will next play fourth-seeded Yevgeny
Kafelnikov of Russia.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since 1985 that the top eight seeds have
all reached the round of 16 at the Canadian event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
