<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gems Miners Urged to Observe Law in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Mines Minister kyaw Min has
urged local gems and jade mining entrepreneurs as well as
merchants to observe the Gemstone Law promulgated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with the entrepreneurs here Thursday, the minister
called on them to cooperate in transport of gems mined in the
country after paying 20 percent tax and receiving inspection and
assessment of their mined gems.
</P>
<P>
The state-run newspaper The New Light of Myanmar today quoted
the minister as saying that some entrepreneurs had smuggled a
large amount of fine quality gems out of the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister warned against the offense which is punishable
with sentences ranging from 10 years to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
According to the Myanmar Gemstone Law, the mined gems and jade
should be sold on the designated Panglong Yadana Gems Market of
the state-run Myanmar Gems Enterprise, with large and fine quality
ones permissible to be sold at two state-sponsored annual gems
emporiums.
</P>
<P>
The law also allows private entrepreneurs to transport and sell
 freely within Myanmar their finished gemstone and manufactured
jewelry or export.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that a five-year national plan envisages
emergence of a gems market in the capital Yangon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
