<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Proposes Faster Privatization for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) have proposed that Thailand
speed up its privatization program and open its commercial banks
to foreign equity holding in excess of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government on Monday decided to seek an emergency
credit line from the IMF and work out an economic revival program.
</P>
<P>
Rescue measures prescribed by IMF economic experts who are now
in Bangkok working with Thai authorities also envisage tax
reforms, flotation of utility rates, higher value-added tax,
strict controls on private sector debt creation and no help for
finance and securities firms.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also wants the Thai currency to stabilize at 30 baht to
the US dollar, the tax base broadened, tax collection improved and
monetary policy tightened.
</P>
<P>
The IMF officials have proposed growth be kept at 4-5 percent,
inflation no more than 7 percent and the current account deficit
no more than 5 percent of gross domestic product, according to
Surasak Nananukul, an adviser to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
However, the package would hurt if implemented in its entirety,
he said, but the government would make counter-proposals to
cushion the impact on the people.
</P>
<P>
Thai Airways International (THAI) and the State Railway of
Thailand have been identified as prime candidates for
privatization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai economists warned on Wednesday the people to
face the pain in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Suwinai Pornvilai, an economist of Thammasat University's
faculty of economics, said the IMF will examine ways for Thailand
to repay debts it owes to international financial institutes, and
will make Thailand increase value-added tax and fees for public
utilities, allow financial institutions with problems to collapse
and cut extravagant expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
