<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes UN Extension of Haitian Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today welcomed
the decision of the United Nations Security Council to create a new UN
Transition Mission in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
"Canada believes that maintaining a UN presence in Haiti will help
consolidate the peace process there and build a solid foundation for
economic development," said Canada's Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd
Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
The new mission will be made up of a civilian police force of 250,
including 60 Canadians, and a military protection force of 1,000, to
which Canada is contributing 650 soldiers
</P>
<P>
It will pick up from the current peacekeeping mission, whose
mandate expires tomorrow, for a four-month mandate until the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
The mission's mandate is to offer protection to the civilian police
officers and contribute to the development of the Haitian National
Police.
</P>
<P>
The UN established a presence in Haiti in March 1995, with Canada
in command since March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new mission is "clearly the last of the peacekeeping missions
there" since Haiti has already indicated that it would make no further
requests for UN peacekeeping troops, according to the Canadian
government. 
</P>
