<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan's GDP Falls Sharply in First Half of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan's gross domestic
product (GDP) slid 29 percent in the first six months of 1997 over
the same period last year, marking the biggest economic decline
among the 12 former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
The figures, released by the State Statistics Committee, showed
that industrial output fell 35.2 percent during the January-June
period.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan's grain harvest was only half the planned 1.2
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan's economy is predominantly agricultural. In recent
years, over-intensive cultivation of the principal crop, cotton,
together with massive irrigation projects, have led to serious
ecological damage.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet meeting today, President Saparmurad Niyazov
demanded better development of the country's potential and asked
integrated agricultural companies to pick no less than 1.4 million
tons of cotton by December 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Now Turkmenistan is leasing farmland to individual farmers on a
long-term basis in a bid to make the country self-sufficient in
food.
</P>
<P>
Compared with other former Soviet republics, Turkmenistan
adopted a more cautious approach towards the implementation of
market economic reforms, concerned that the population's living
standards should not, as a consequence, deteriorate drastically.
</P>
<P>
The privatization of state property in the country, to be
effected in three stages, started only in December 1993,
considerably later than in other republics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
