<HEADLINE> Sexual Harassment, Crime in Southern Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Strides have been made in most
Southern African Development Community (SADC) member states to
recognize sexual harassment as a criminal offense, gender
activist Patricia Mcfadden said here today.
</P>
<P>
Mcfadden said there had been significant progress since the
program to make sexual harassment a crime was introduced at
various universities in the region three years ago.
</P>
<P>
''There is an active network in the region in which women are
fighting back, insisting that sexual harassment be recognized as
a criminal offense,'' the South African activist said at the
four-day conference on the girl child which ends Thursday.
</P>
<P>
She said the effects of sexual harassment were far reaching as
the victims suffered psychologically and physically.
</P>
<P>
''It's more than just touching, it's also a violation of the
integrity,'' she said, adding that it was an imposition of sexism
and an expression of male supremacy.
</P>
<P>
It is difficult to fight sexual harassment because it has been
culturalized, she said, with men who normally are among the
violators, often arguing that it is cultural to admire and touch
women even against their will.
</P>
<P>
The program, she said, was strategically targeted at
universities as the graduates would be future industrialists.
</P>
</TEXT>
