<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Convertible Bonds Trade Reaches Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 30 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has issued more
convertible bonds this year, with the trade volume of such bonds
so far this year reaching a record high of 2.07 trillion won
(about 2.33 billion U.S. dollars), the Korea Stock Exchange (KSE)
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume of convertible bonds as of July 29 this year,
the highest since the trade began to be concentrated at the KSE in
1994, exceeded the 1996 total of 1.13 trillion won (1.27 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the volume registered a slip of 2.59 percent from 1.16
trillion won (1.30 billion dollars ) the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The issuance of convertible bonds, which had declined steadily
since 1994, also increased remarkably this year, with 931.8
billion won (1.05 billion dollars) worth of bonds issued as of
July 29, already approaching the 1996 total of 1.02 trillion won
(1.15 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Market observers attributed the rise to increased participation
by individual and foreign investors, as well as the successive
foreign investment limit hikes over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Issuance of convertible bonds is favored more than ever, due
to increased hopes of a market recovery after a long-term bear
market, they said.
</P>
<P>
Changes in bonds trade regulations, which allow investors to
convert their holdings into stocks after three months, instead of
the previous six months, have also added to the appeal of such
bonds, they added.
</P>
<P>
They predicted the trend to continue for the rest of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
