<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House of Representatives Passes Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Tuesday passed a defense bill of 248 billion
dollars which is to fund new military hardware and increase
military pay, but would halt U.S. ground operations in Bosnia
after June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved by a vote of 322-105 in the house, would
demand some four billion dollars more than the Clinton
administration planned for hardware and equipment, and 770 million
more for research and development programs.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton has threatened to veto the bill, which
was 4.4 billion dollars more than his budget request and 3.9
billion more than this year's military spending.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, the United States would spend 505 million
dollars on B-52 bombers this year, an increase of 331 million
dollars over last year, and 3.67 billion dollars on missile
defense programs.
</P>
<P>
The bill would also allow 79 million dollars for the Defense
Department programs dealing with the Gulf War-related
events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
