<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three English Men for Murder Convictions Exonerated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The English Court of Appeal today
exonerated three men who spent 18 years in prison for the murder
of a newspaper delivery boy.
</P>
<P>
The court quashed the convictions of Michael Hickey, his cousin
Vincent, James Robinson and a fourth defendant Patrick Molloy, who
died in prison in 1981, for the murder of 13-year-old Carl
Bridgewater, shot dead during a robbery in 1978.
</P>
<P>
"We have concluded that the appellants did not have a fair
trial and for that reason have quashed their convictions," Lord
Justice John Roch told the court.
</P>
<P>
"This is another case of a miscarriage of justice which is a
matter of regret for this court," he added.
</P>
<P>
The three men were released on unconditional bail in February
after prosecution lawyers said their trial was fundamentally
flawed and the convictions unsafe.
</P>
<P>
The men, known as the Bridgewater Four, had always protested
their innocence and had staged hunger strikes during their
imprisonment. Now they are seeking compensations for their 18-year
wrongful sentence.
</P>
<P>
During the one-month appeal hearing, lawyer Michael Mansfield
accused police of tricking Molloy into signing a false confession
and said a squad of police officers had conducted a carefully
cultivated strategy of deception.
</P>
<P>
The Appeal Court ruled that Molloy's confession had probably
been obtained by deceit and was inadmissable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
