<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: It's a Win-Win for EU and Boeing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Though the European Commission
pronounced the go-ahead to the Boeing-McDonnell Douglas merger,
concessions were made as much if not more on the American side
than from across the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
A damaging trade war was averted at last after seven months of
paperwork and negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The environment for competition was seemingly rendered more
fair as the Europeans okayed the move on conditions that Boeing
cedes all its existing and would-be exclusive supply deals, or at
least it has to refrain from such exclusivity until the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
This, alongside Boeing commitment not to abuse relationship
with customers and suppliers, is hoped to leave some leeway for
Airbus to land some orders in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans also required McDonnell Douglas to "fence" up its
commercial aircraft activities and they themselves, too, can use
through the licensing mechanism the aeronautic patents developed
under the auspices of U.S. governmental subsidy and public
funding.
</P>
<P>
All told, Boeing has made "substantial" concessions that took
care of Union officials' main concerns and led to the anti-trust
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Although the American aircraft makers backstepped from the
starting line of another round of competition in the global
aircraft market, the Europeans do not look to having a feasible
chance to get abreast with their American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Now that the completion of the Boeing-MD merger is only a
matter of time, their carriers will soon expand from the current
Boeing market share of 64 percent to a combined 70 percent while
their share in the service fleet worldwide is to rise from 60
percent to a dazzling, if not damaging, 84 percent.
</P>
<P>
And what's more, the Boeing-MD combined market share is about
two thirds of the EU market, where airlines are forecast to
account for almost a third of future demands for commercial
aircraft over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
By grabbing for itself a market sharing opportunity with
billions upon billions of ECUs or Euros looming on the horizon,
the European Union has also reciprocated more of the bonanza to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
But should things go wrong after 2007, trade rows are destined
to return to between Boeing-MD and its archrival in the European
continent, the Airbus consortium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
