<HEADLINE> Alatas: No Deadline for Cambodia's Entry into ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's entry into the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) is still awaiting
the agreement of two conflicting parties in Cambodia, Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The membership of ASEAN might be determined during Cambodia's
election in May 1998, or before or after the poll when the two
warring factions in that country reach an agreement. No deadline
has been set for Cambodia's entry," he said after having talks
with his Canadian counterpart Llyod Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy arrived here Tuesday for a three-day visit to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar. Cambodia was
delayed to enter the grouping because of political crisis in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Alatas along with Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn and
Philippine Foreign Minister Domingo Siazon plan to meet Cambodia's
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen in Phnom Penh late this week.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, ASEAN is interested in helping to end the crisis in
Cambodia, but this is not the right time for me to tell the
press," he said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas did not elaborate on the topics the three ministers will
discuss with Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, an agreement between the two warring
factions, namely, the Cambodian People's Party (CCP) led by Hun
Sen and FUNCINPEC led by First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh,
plays a significant role in ending the Cambodian crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said a formation of a coalition cabinet and Cambodia's
election next year are two important factors to end the conflict.
"Whoever wins the election should be acknowledged by the Cambodian
people," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
