<HEADLINE> Egypt Condemns Jerusalem Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt strongly denounced today the
two bomb explosions that rocked a bustling market in Jerusalem,
killing 13 people and wounding more than 150, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak condemned the two deadly
bombings as "a sabotage" to the peace process and conveyed his
condolences to relatives of the victims.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian stance is clear, which denounces all kinds of
violence that works against the Mideast peace process," Mubarak
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader said he had had telephone contacts with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and President Ezer
Weizman after the bloody suicide bombings which took place at
around 10:15 GMT.
</P>
<P>
In another telephone conversation with Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat after the tragedy, Mubarak said
he stressed the importance of going all out to fight back "those
provocations against the efforts to save Mideast peace."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa also expressed his condolences to
families of the victims and said the bombings "apparently do not
contribute to peace."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that all kinds of perpetrations against the peace
process have wrecked great pains upon both Palestinians and
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The peace process should not be stopped, he said, adding that
"At this crucial time, it is important to continue the efforts to
achieve just and lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
Moussa also called for "restraint" from all parties in the
aftermath of the deadly bombings. "I hope all peace-loving people,
especially those in Israel, to cling to saving the peace process,
which is the only way to safeguard their security," he noted.
</P>
<P>
So far no one has claimed responsibility for the suicide
bombings in the main fruit and vegetable market in West
Jerusalem. But Israel blamed them on Palestinian militants which
oppose peace with Israel and have launched similar attacks in the
past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
