<HEADLINE> S. Africa Condemns Jerusalem Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today condemned
a suicide bombing in West Jerusalem, in which 18 people were
killed and more than 150 others injured.
</P>
<P>
In its statement, the South African Foreign Affairs Department
described the bombing as "a despicable atrocity", and urged
parties concerned to avoid any actions or retaliation which might
exacerbate tensions, and to continue with peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The statement said it is time for all people of goodwill in
the region to address their differences through dialogue and to
accept that the only road to a lasting and just peace lies in
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The statement also expressed regret at the loss of life and
extended condolences to those injured and the families of those
killed.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, shortly after midday
today, two bombs exploded in Jerusalem's busiest Mahane Yehuda
open market, killing at least 18 people and wounded 150 others.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility yet for the attacks, but
police suspected they were suicide bombings carried out by
Palestinian extremists. 
</P>
