<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Urges Arafat To Take Stiff Anti-Terror </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu today urged Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to take
stiff anti-terror actions following two bomb explosions in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We expect not words of consolation from the Palestinian
Authority. What we expect is action to apprehend these terrorists
and their leaders," said Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu announced the statement when he was addressing a
hastily-arranged press conference following the twin bomb
explosions in the central open market in Jerusalem this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A total of 14 people, apparently including two suicide bombers,
were killed and 170 were injured. The incident is the most serious
one in terms of casualties since he came to power more than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the bombing attack, Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat telephoned Netanyahu condemning the attack and expressing
condolences to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Referring apparently to Arafat's gestures, Netanyahu said in
his statement that Israel needs cooperation from the
PNA. "Security cooperation can stop terrorism," he added.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said, the PNA released some 150 terrorists of Hamas
and Islamic Jihad and they were set free to approach Israel's
cities and streets and commit barbarous acts.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said: "we expect action to collect explosives and
weapons. They are there in the field and can be collected."
</P>
<P>
The premier concluded: "I expect (from the PNA) not words of
condolence alone, words of condemnation alone, words of reproach
alone, but words that educate and call on the Palestinian
population to rise against terrorism." "That is what we expect
and we have every right to expect that," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
