<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges Revitalization of China-aided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Zambia have no
plans to privatize the China-aided joint Tanzania-Zambia railway
(TAZARA) but would further commercialize and revitalize it,
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here this afternoon at the end of his
three-day state visit, Chiluba said TAZARA has been privatized
enough and the immediate task is to raise efficiency and
innovativeness.
</P>
<P>
"We are not talking about privatization of TAZARA. Our goal is
to enhance efficiency and enable TAZARA to compete effectively in
this liberalized market," the Zambian president said.
</P>
<P>
He paid tribute to the founding fathers of the two nations,
Julius Nyerere and Kenith Kaunda, saying the spirit of TAZARA
must not be killed by those running the entity.
</P>
<P>
"If the management lacks innovativeness and enterprise then
something must be done about it," said Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two presidents have urged the private sector to
boost economic production, trade and investments in agriculture,
manufacturing industry, small-scale mining, communication,
transport and tourism.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint communique issued here today, the two
presidents have also agreed to reactivate the sub-commission on
trade, industry and finance to facilitate and promote cooperation
in trade, industry and finance.
</P>
<P>
They further agreed on improving the performance of the two
jointly-owned institutions, TAZARA and the Tanzania-Zambia
Pipeline (TAZAMA).
</P>
<P>
On regional issues, the two presidents reaffirmed support for
the decisions made on Burundi on April 16 this year, during the
fourth Arusha regional summit.
</P>
<P>
However, they expressed regret that the installation of the
government of national unity and reconstruction in Angola had so
far not led to the restoration of permanent peace and stability
in that country.
</P>
<P>
They expressed concern at the resumption of fighting in some
parts of the country and called upon the parties to the conflict
to adhere to the letter and spirit of the Lusaka protocol of
November in 1994.
</P>
<P>
On Liberia, the two presidents welcomed the holding of free
and fair elections and urged the people to embark upon the
reconstruction of their country.
</P>
<P>
President Chiluba and his delegation left for home after the
press conference and were seen off at the Dar es Salaam
International Airport by President Mkapa and other senior
government officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
