<HEADLINE> Angolan Women Voice Their Demand for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
(by Yin Yongjian)
</P>
<P>
LUANDA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of women in the
war-plagued southern African country took to the street today
crying for their long-awaited peace.
</P>
<P>
Carrying placards inscribed with "We Want Peace, Not War",
"Stop Violence", "Build A Beautiful Future For Our Descendants"#,
these women marched to the national congress building of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Many of the demonstrators are women who have lost their
husbands or children in the two decades civil war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators walked to the front of the national
congress building where parliament members were having a meeting
and presented their letter for peace.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that the Angolan women who have suffered most
from the war in the country would sacrifice whatever they have
for a final peace, so that their younger generations would no
longer fight each other in the meaningless wars.
</P>
<P>
Analia Pereira, a woman parliament member said that "we, the
mothers who have suffered physically and spiritually in the wars
and lost our children should be safeguards for peace."
</P>
<P>
She said that "Angolan women should, joining hands with
Angolan men, strive for the final peace in the country, and never
allow the tragedy of war to befall on the land again."
</P>
<P>
The peace demonstration was organized to mark the African
Women's Day on July 31. Women in some other cities in the
war-ridden country also held similar activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
