<HEADLINE> ACP-EU Partnership to Be Based on "Co-operation" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Jinyu)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia
Mudavadi said today that the new partnership between
African-Caribbean-Pacific countries and European Union (ACP-EU)
should be based on true "cooperation" rather than on
"assistance".
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the closing session of the Eastern Africa
Regional Seminar on the Future of the ACP-EU Cooperation held
here between July 28-30.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that unprecedented changes had taken place
worldwide since the first Lome Convention signed between ACP
countries and EU 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
One of the changes is that "development assistance seems to
have lost its priority on the political agenda of many European
countries," he told the seminar held to discuss the future ACP-EU
relations after the expiry of the Lome IV Convention.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi pointed out that a number of donors had indeed
reduced their financial support to the third world, adding that
"it is our urgent duty to be aware of the effects of this trend."
</P>
<P>
He viewed the seminar as "an important step" in the long
process of re-defining, re-structuring and updating the terms of
this partnership established 22 years ago between the ACP
countries and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the geographical scope and coverage of the
convention should be maintained and consolidated in a future
ACP-EU agreement.
</P>
<P>
The differentiation of aid portfolios should be in accordance
with the needs, strategies and capacities of recipient countries,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that conditionalities should be a series
of well negotiated, transparent and positive goals rather than a
set of absolute punitive measures applied to ACP countries.
</P>
<P>
This regional seminar was designed to shape the common
position of the eastern African region towards the post-Lome
Convention debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
