<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Ask EU Membership Talks Be Put off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Northern Cyprus leader Rauf
Denktas said today the European Union's negotiations with Cyprus
for its full membership should be postponed to enable
U.N.-brokered direct bi-communal talks to continue.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here today, Denktas said the
decision to demand the postponement of EU-Cyprus membership talks
was taken unanimously by the administration of northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The east Mediterranean island has been divided into Greek
Cypriot south and Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkey
landed troops to protect Turkish Cypriots following a pro-Athens
coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
After the two ethnic groups agreed to hold face-to-face talks
under U.N. sponsorship at the beginning of this month, the EU
executive body European Commission gave the green-light to Cyprus'
full EU membership talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktas requested EU to put off the negotiations for Cyprus'
entry scheduled for 1998. "Otherwise, U.N.-mediated Cyprus talks
will stop," he threatened.
</P>
<P>
Clerides has said the Greek Cypriots would not take part in the
peace talks if the negotiations with EU are postponed.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 and the
Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 Turkish troops are stationed in the northern
part of the divided Mediterranean island to safeguard the security
of the Turkish Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-30 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
