<HEADLINE> Hussein Called for Efforts to Prevent Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan today called
for all efforts to salvage the Middle East peace process and
prevent violence such as this afternoon's suicide bombings in the
West Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blasts came at a time of frustration about the
stalled peace process, the king said in an address to the
graduate officers from the Royal Award Academy, Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
No one knows the consequences of these incidents, he said,
adding minority groups were trying to tide up anti-Jewish
sentiments but they would not succeed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, a Jordanian government spokesman condemned this
afternoon's suicide bombings in the West Jerusalem as terrorist
activity against the innocent people.
</P>
<P>
Two suicide bombs exploded at 13:15 this afternoon in an open
market in the West Jerusalem, killing 14 people, including the
two bombers and wounding more than 170.
</P>
<P>
This was the first suicide bombing attack since the March 22
suicide bombing of a Tel Aviv cafe and one of the worst terror
attacks against Israel since the peace process began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blasts came at a time when the Palestinians and
Israelis had agreed to resume peace talks this week, giving hope
to break the prolonged deadlock in the peace talks, which have
been stalled since Israel started building the Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The long-term implications of the bombings remained unclear at
the time, but the immediate setback was the cancellation of a
planned visit to the region tomorrow by U.S. special peace envoy
Dennis Ross on a new round of mediation. Washington announced to
postpone Ross' mission shortly after the bombing attacks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that even if lower-level talks between the
Palestinians and the Israelis would be resumed as scheduled, no
major progress could be made when the two sides remained dubious
about each other's commitments to peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
