<HEADLINE> OHADA Headquarters to be Based in Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for the
Harmonization of Business Rights in Africa (OHADA) will have its
headquarters in Cameroun, local radio reported here today.
</P>
<P>
An accord to inaugurate the OHADA headquarters of permanent
secretariat was signed in Yaounde this morning between the
Camerounian government and the officials of the OHADA.
</P>
<P>
Minister of External Relations of Cameroun Ferdinand Oyono and
Argeba Polo, the Ohada's permanent secretary inked the accord.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun is among the 16 African states that signed the treaty
creating the organization in 1993 on the island of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
As an organization with technical, industrial and commercial
vocation, the OHADA is responsible for the settlement of business
dispute among the 16 member countries in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The OHADA, whose aim is to adopt appropriate legal structures
governing economic development policy in Africa, is made up of
three main institutions: the Permanent Secretariat based in
Cameroun; the Court of Justice and Arbitration in Cote d'Ivoire
and the School of Magistracy in Benin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
