<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-30 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Parliamentary Elections to Be Held As </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 30 (Xinhua) - Jordan's King Hussein said here today
that parliamentary elections will take place as "constitutionally
scheduled," despite declared boycott by six opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan quoted the king as saying democracy would
continue in the kingdom despite any opposition while addressing
graduate officers from the Royal Award Academy.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government has decided to invite international
observers to oversee the elections due on November 4 in an effort
to defuse uproar from six opposition parties to boycott the
elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Muslim Brotherhood, a main opposition
party, became the first to declare boycott of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Its general supervisor Abdul Majeed Thneibat said on July 12
that the Press and Publication Law, the one-person, one-vote
election system, the normalization of ties with Israel, and "the
government's measures to marginalize political parties" were the
main reasons behind the party's boycott of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Later, five parties followed suit. They are the Jordan
People's Democratic Party, the Jordan Arab Constitutional Front,
the National Action Front, the Al Ansar and the Islamic Action
Front (IAF), the biggest opposition party in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The boycott is also supported by some other parties, which have
yet to declare whether they wanted to join in. Opposition parties
now own 23 seats in the 80-member Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Multi-party system was revived in the kingdom in 1989 as part
of a political reform launched after widespread riots that were
set off by economic hardships. The protesters called for wider
public participation in decision-making. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
