<HEADLINE> Security Council Hails Successful Elections in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations today welcomed the successful holding of
presidential and legislative elections in Liberia on July 19,
1997.
</P>
<P>
In its presidential statement, the Security Council said that
the electoral process was free, fair, and credible, and that the
outcome of the elections reflected the will of the Liberian voters.
</P>
<P>
The council called upon all parties to abide by the results of
the elections and to cooperate in the formation of a new
government. It called upon the new government to protect the
democratic system and to promote human rights and fundamental
freedom under the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council welcomed the goodwill and cooperation
demonstrated by the parties in the electoral process, which
provided a strong foundation for the people of Liberia to achieve
a durable peace, the re-establishment of constitutional
government, and a return to the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed the hope that the successful holding of
election would encourage refugees to exercise their rights of
return, and it called upon the new government to fulfill its
obligations under international law regarding returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
Noting the successful holding of elections represented a
critical step towards economic development, the council urged
the international society to continue to provide support and
assistance to Liberia through this period of reconstruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
