<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Announces Initiatives to Meet Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- British business needs to work in
new ways if it is to make the most of the opportunities offered by
electronic commerce and the information age, Adair Turner,
director-general of the Confederation of British Industry (CBI),
said today.
</P>
<P>
Launching both the CBI's own website and a new CBI initiative
to spread best practice, Turner said that the UK is well-placed to
be a global leader in the information society.
</P>
<P>
With a total output of 57.6 billion US dollars, growing at
around 7 percent a year, the UK's electronic and IT equipment
sector is the sixth largest in the world and is a major source of
innovation.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the top 20 investors in R&AMP;D in the UK are electronics,
IT or telecommunications companies, said Turner.
</P>
<P>
The markets open to electronic commerce are considerable and
are set to grow at a remarkable pace. Fifty million people in 150
countries are already connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that by the year 2000 there will be 250 million
subscribers and the US marketplace alone will be worth 112 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Companies need to develop completely new ways of thinking and
acting to take advantage of these new markets," Turner said. "The
overall growth potential is huge, but the way in which these
markets will develop is still very unclear - that means both big
risks, but also big rewards."
</P>
<P>
Turner spelt out the issues business needs to consider as a
result of the rapid growth in information and communication:
</P>
<P>
-- The very rapid development of new technologies;
</P>
<P>
-- The convergence of different technologies --
</P>
<P>
telecommunications, electronics, multimedia and broadcasting;
</P>
<P>
-- The growing global business competition;
</P>
<P>
-- The urgent need for people with the right IT skills and
</P>
<P>
attitudes.
</P>
<P>
Turner said, "It's not enough simply to put information about
yourself on the Internet and think you're participating in the
information age. The potential is there to do your business
electronically -- and that's where the big benefits may well lie."
</P>
<P>
He also announced the setting up of the CBI's information
society forum. This is designed to spread best practice and help
member companies address the implications of the information age.
</P>
<P>
It responds to fast-growing member interest, and will focus on
such topics as technology in the retail supply chain, knowledge
management and valuation, the creative use of technology, as well
as a whole series on the specific challenges facing smaller firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Decides to Establish New Mission in Haiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council decided today to establish the United Nations Transmission
Mission in Haiti (UNTMIH) to help the state train its national
police force.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution unanimously adopted this afternoon, the
Security Council affirmed the importance of a professional,
self-sustaining, fully functioning national police force of
adequate size and structure, able to conduct the full spectrum of
police functions, to the consolidation of democracy and the
revitalization of Haiti's system of justice.
</P>
<P>
The UNTMIH would shoulder a mandate limited to a single
four-month period ending November 30 in order to assist the
Haitian government by supporting and contributing to the
professionalization of the Haitian National Police, according to
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
On the size of the new mission, the Security Council decided
that the UNTMIH be composed of up to 250 civilian police and 50
military personnel to form the headquarters of a security element.
</P>
<P>
The UNTMIH would also assume responsibility for all elements
and assets of the United Nations Support Mission in Haiti (UNSMIH)
remaining in Haiti to deploy as appropriate until they are
withdrawn. The mandate of the UNSMIH would terminate on July 31,
according to the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing that economic rehabilitation and reconstruction
constitute the major tasks facing the Haitian government and
people, the council stressed the commitment of the international
community to a long-term program of support for Haiti.
</P>
<P>
The council also requested all states to make voluntary
contributions to the trust fund for the Haitian National Police,
in particular for the recruitment and deployment of police
advisers to assist inspector general, directorate general and
department headquarters of the Haitian National Police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
