<HEADLINE> UK's Blair Clashes with Hague over Minister's Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
today clashed with Conservative Party leader William Hague by
accusing him of spreading "vile and scurrilous" slurs in a
minister's share affairs.
</P>
<P>
While answering questions in parliament, Blair repeatedly asked
Hague to produce evidence that the minister had broken rules or to
withdraw his allegations.
</P>
<P>
Hague accused Lord David Simon, chairman of British Petroleum
Plc, of avoiding tax by holding one million pounds (1.64 million
U.S. dollars) worth of shares in an offshore trust. Simon joined
the Labor government in May as unpaid Minister for Trade and
Competitiveness in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Hague, who replaced former prime minister John Major as the
largest opposition Conservative Party last month, said he detected
"a strong smell of hypocrisy from the government benches".
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there has been a more vile and scurrilous
campaign than the one mounted against David Simon," Blair said of
Hague's accusation.
</P>
<P>
"Because under the previous government there were allegations
proven of misconduct they want to try to smear the new government,
to pretend all politics is the same. Well, all politics is not the
same and this Labor government is not that Tory government," Blair
said. 
</P>
