<HEADLINE> UNDP Launches Programs to Assist Tanzania, Bhutan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program has launched a 13 million dollar program to
help Tanzania meet its goal of eradicating absolute poverty by the
year 2010, according to the latest UNDP Flash.
</P>
<P>
The initiative will strengthen civil society organizations
working locally to fight poverty through community initiatives,
and will build their alliances with the government.
</P>
<P>
Funding will also promote better aid coordination, capacity
building, advocacy and effective monitoring and evaluation of
economic and social conditions. Almost 50 percent of Tanzania's
population of 30 million live below the poverty line. High infant
mortality rates, malnutrition, lack of access to safe water and
environmental degradation contribute to widespread poverty.
</P>
<P>
The latest publication of UNDP also reported that UNDP has
approved a 6.5 million dollar program to improve horticultural
development in rural areas of Bhutan, with the objective of
improving income, living and nutritional standards among the
country's rural poor. The assistance will focus on strengthening
several critical aspects of the industry, including marketing,
post harvest storage, quality control, production technology,
extension services and processing of aromatic and medicinal
plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
