<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns of Lebanon Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department on
Wednesday cautioned American citizens against traveling to
Lebanon after Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has allowed a
ten-year ban on visits to expire.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the announcement on her way back from Asia after
receiving assurances from Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri's
government it would cooperate "across the board" to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But the State Department said expiration of the ban to travel
"should not in any way be construed as a determination by the
Department of State that it is safe for Americans to travel to
Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
A department travel advisory said American citizens who go to
Lebanon despite the warning "should exercise extreme caution and
avoid traveling in the southern suburbs of Beirut, the Bekaa
valley and southern Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
The United States imposed the ban to travel to Lebanon in
1987 after hostage taking and numerous other attacks by
anti-American militants. 
