<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Again Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
voiced on Wednesday his strong support for an effort to bring a
bipartisan reform bill sponsored by Senators John McCain, a
Republican from Arisona, and Russell Feingold, a Democrat from
Wisconsin, before Congress for a vote in September.
</P>
<P>
The bill would ban unregulated "soft money" raised from special
interests by political parties, tighten restriction on political
action committees and offer incentives such as free and
reduced-cost television time to encourage compliance with
voluntary spending limits.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement Clinton said, "September will be the
time for members of the Senate to stand up and be counted for
reform. I will do what I can to see to it that 1997 is finally the
year that it is achieved."
</P>
<P>
Clinton blamed excessive fund-raising practices on "the special
interests and their allies."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "This year, those who seek to continue special
interest influence as usual will filibuster again. But this year,
we have an opportunity to come together across party lines to act
and pass reform that cleans up the campaign finance system."
</P>
</TEXT>
