<HEADLINE> Albright: Arafat Committed to Restoring Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said on Wednesday that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
has assured her to commit himself to "restore a secure atmosphere"
after two bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her way back from a trip to Asia, said in
Honolulu, Hawaii, that she called Arafat from her U.S. Air Force
jet and was assured by Arafat that "he was committed to restoring
a secure atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
The two bombings occurred at a crowded market in Jerusalem on
Wednesday afternoon that killed 14 Israeli people and wounded more
than 150.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the Palestinian leader "condemned the act" and
was meeting his security officials. Arafat "said to me they were
doing everything they could to make sure the security situation is
restored," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright also called Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu. "We talked about the importance of returning to the
peace process and I urged him to do so and he said he understood
the importance of returning to the peace process ... He did say
he would," she said. 
</P>
