<DOCNO> XIE19970731.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Peru's Record Industry Losing Millions to Pirates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The record industry in Peru has lost
400 million U.S. dollars over the past 10 years due to piracy, a
music industry executive said today.
</P>
<P>
For every legal cassette, there are 12 pirated copies, which
means more than 90 percent of the cassettes on the market are
counterfeit, said Guillermo Bracamonte, legal counsellor of Latin
American Federation of Audio and Videocassette Productions.
</P>
<P>
With sales of compact discs now outstripping cassettes,
counterfeiters have turned to producing pirated CDs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Peru imports 10 million blank cassettes every year, said
Bracamonte. But the legal record industry sells an average of
800,000, the remaining 9.2 million cassettes are used for pirated
recordings.
</P>
<P>
The amount lost lies not only in the sales of cassettes but in
the payment of recording royalties, explained Bracamonte. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
