<HEADLINE> Mexican Companies Deny Plans to Quit Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Three Mexican multinational
companies in Costa Rica today denied newspaper reports they would
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Mabe, a household appliances manufacturer, ICA and Tribasa, two
construction companies, confirmed they would continue their
business in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Last October, a Costa Rican company producing refrigerators
filed a complaint against Mabe with the economy ministry. Although
the company withdrew its complaint in March, the ministry
continued its investigation, although no results have been made
public.
</P>
<P>
ICA participated in the building of the Angostura Dam, an major
project of the state-owned Costa Rica Electricity Institute.
Although it's widely believed ICA is owed money for the project,
the company maintains its intention to invest in Costa Rica,
the Costa Rican newspaper "la Nacion" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tribasa case has political repercussions since doubts
have emerged about Carlos Hank, a Mexican businessman and
politician who has ties with the company.
</P>
<P>
The Controller General's Office of Costa Rica annulled the bid
Tribasa won to rebuild part of the inter-American highway in the
midst of a scandal involving Hank and for his ties with important
opposition politicians here.
</P>
<P>
A Tribasa spokesperson denied the company is thinking of leaving
the country while the Controller General's Office is trying to
settle the problems that originated from the annullment of the
winning bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
