<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Flooded Area Faces Another Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- About 15,000 people was told today to
be ready to abandon their homes at a moment's notice after the
swollen Oder River on the German-Polish border threatened to flood
a vast low-lying area of eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 troops who had been fighting a losing battle
overnight to save the weakening dikes in the northern part of the
Oder were forced to retreat from the riverside when a
50-meter-long stretch of dike was torn open by floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the dikes at Hohenwutzen in the Oderbruch
region had partially collapsed, but the situation was not yet
totally hopeless. Helicopters were still dropping sandbags to try
to block the gap.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, rescue workers were still laboring to pile up
sandbags along another dike in the background which would serve as
a second defense against floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Although no serious dike damages were reported in other parts
of the Oder, authorities said it was uncertain whether they could
cope with another wave of high water expected to come soon.
</P>
<P>
It had already been a miracle that the sodden dikes had managed
to withstand the huge pressure of the water mass for the past two
weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
To make things worse, weather forecasters on Wednesday
predicted scattered heavy thundershowers for the region into the
weekend. The swollen river would not ebb until next week, experts
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
