<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Sets New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks advanced to new
highs today as bond-market interest rates sank to their lowest
level in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average added 80.36 points to 8,254.89
for its third consecutive record high and its sixth in seven
sessions.
</P>
<P>
The Dow surpassed 8,200 mark just two weeks after its first
close above 8,000.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 568.48
million shares as against 544.55 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 10.00 to 952.29, the
NYSE composite index rose 5.14 to 645.32, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index rose 5.12 to 645.32. All three measures
closed at record highs on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 15.73 to 1,588.05, beating its
previous record finish at 1,580.63 on July 16.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip gauge has now risen about 28 percent this year,
already surpassing last year's 26 percent advance and triple what
many experts had forecast.
</P>
<P>
Stocks drew most of their strength from the bond market, where
the yield on the 30-year Treasury fell to 6.32 percent. The
long-bond yield hasn't finished a day that low since February
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported that new home sales jumped 6.1
percent to 819,000 in June to the highest level since March,
spurred by favorable mortgage rates and solid job and income
growth. The May tally, however, was revised downward from 825,000
to 772,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
