<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Peace Envoy Return to Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. peace mediator on
Bosnia Richard Holbrooke will visit the Balkans next week as part
of a U.S. team that will press for implementation of the Dayton
peace accords, the State Department announced today.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke will join a U.S. team led by Robert Gelbard, U.S.
special representative for Dayton implementation, and would visit
Bosnia, Serbia and Croatia, said State Department spokesman James
Foley.
</P>
<P>
He said the mission would discuss U.S. concerns about
implementation of the agreement, which was reached in November
1995 largely thanks to the efforts of Holbrooke, who was an
assistant secretary of state at the time.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, expected to include State Department, Pentagon
and National Security Council officials, would travel to the
region and meet key Balkan leaders.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke quit government service in February 1996 to join
Credit Suisse First Boston bank, a position he still holds. He was
recently appointed a part-time U.S. envoy on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The aim of sending the team to Bosnia "clearly is to send a
very strong signal to the parties of our very strong expectation
that they get with it on Dayton implementation," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
The move reflects the U.S.'s anxiety that unless the major
elements of the accords were fully implemented, it will be
difficult for the U.S. and its allies to withdraw all their troops
out of the region by next June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
