<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Announces Plan to Reduce Troops in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain
Richard today announced that France plans to reduce its
8,000-strong military deployment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
But he said that Paris will reinforce its means for staging
quick reaction operations in the black continent, like the Pelican
operation launched by French troops in Brazzaville last month to
evacuate foreigners from the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
Richard said in Libreville, capital of Gabon, which is the
first stop of his three-nation Africa tour, that the "global
number" of French troops will drop, but the means of transport and
projection of forces will increase, according to Agence
France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
He said that France will re-shuffle its troop deployments in
all the African states where it has military bases.
</P>
<P>
Richard refused to say whether France will close the Bouar
military base in the Central African Republic, which is one of
France's six permanent military bases in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said that the military agreements between France and some
African states are too old and can no longer respond to the
"political objectives" of France.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Figaro said that France will first withdraw its
1,400 troops based in the Central African Republic, as the first
step of a 40 percent reduction of its forces in Africa.
</P>
<P>
France now has 3,400 troops stationed in Djibouti, 1,400 in the
Central African Republic, 1,200 in Senegal, 800 in Chad, 600 in
Gabon and 600 in Cote d'Ivoire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
